# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brooklyn-new-york
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The borough, as Kings County, at 37,339.9 inhabitants per square mile (14,417.0/km2), is the second most densely populated county in the U.S. after Manhattan (New York County), and the most populous county in the state, as of 2022.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In the 2020 United States census, the borough had a population of 2,736,074.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Had Brooklyn remained an independent city on Long Island, it would now be the fourth most populous American city after the rest of New York City, Los Angeles, and Chicago.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn, named after the Dutch town of Breukelen in the Netherlands, was founded by the Dutch in the 17th century and grew into a busy port city on New York Harbor by the 19th century.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The borough continues to maintain a distinct culture.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Many Brooklyn neighborhoods are ethnic enclaves.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] With Jews forming around a fifth of its population, the borough has been described as one of the main global hubs for Jewish culture.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn's official motto, displayed on the borough seal and flag, is *Een Draght Mackt Maght*, which translates from early modern Dutch as "In unity there is strength".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Educational institutions in Brooklyn include the City University of New York's Brooklyn College, Medgar Evers College, and College of Technology, as well as Pratt Institute, Long Island University, and the New York University Tandon School of Engineering.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In sports, basketball's Brooklyn Nets, and New York Liberty play at the Barclays Center.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In the first decades of the 21st century, Brooklyn has experienced a renaissance as a destination for hipsters, with associated gentrification, dramatic house-price increases, and a decrease in housing affordability.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Some new developments are now required to include affordable housing units.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Since the 2010s, parts of Brooklyn have evolved into a hub for entrepreneurship, high-technology startup firms, postmodern art, and design.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The name Brooklyn is derived from the original Dutch town of Breukelen.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] This form is made up of the words *broeck*, meaning bog or marshland, and *lede*, meaning small (dug) water stream, specifically in peat areas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Breuckelen on the American continent was established in 1646, and the name first appeared in print in 1663.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Over the past two millennia, the name of the ancient town in Holland has been *Bracola*, *Broccke*, *Brocckede*, *Broiclede*, *Brocklandia*, *Broekclen*, *Broikelen*, *Breuckelen*, and finally *Breukelen*.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The New Amsterdam settlement of *Breuckelen* also went through many spelling variations, including *Breucklyn*, *Breuckland*, *Brucklyn*, *Broucklyn*, *Brookland*, *Brockland*, *Brocklin*, and *Brookline/Brook-line*.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] There have been so many variations of the name that its origin has been debated; some have claimed *breuckelen* means "broken land".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The current name, however, is the one that best reflects its meaning.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The county's name, **Kings County**, was named after King Charles II of England, who ruled from 1660 to 1685.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The history of European settlement in Brooklyn spans more than 350 years.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The Dutch were the first Europeans to settle Long Island's western edge, which was then largely inhabited by the Lenape, an Algonquian-speaking American Indian tribe often referred to in European documents by a variation of the place name "Canarsie".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Bands were associated with place names, but the colonists thought their names represented different tribes.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The *Breuckelen* settlement was named after Breukelen in the Netherlands; it was part of New Netherland.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The colony's capital of New Amsterdam, across the East River, obtained its charter in 1653.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The neighborhood of Marine Park was home to North America's first tide mill.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] It was built by the Dutch, and the foundation can be seen today.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] But the area was not formally settled as a town.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Many incidents and documents relating to this period are in Gabriel Furman's 1824 compilation.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Present-day Brooklyn left Dutch hands after the English conquest of New Netherland in 1664, which sparked the Second Anglo-Dutch War.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] New Netherland was taken in a naval action, and the English renamed the new capture for their naval commander, James, Duke of York, brother of the then monarch King Charles II and future king himself as King James II.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn became a part of the West Riding of York Shire in the Province of New York, one of the Middle Colonies in England's North American colonies.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] On November 1, 1683, *Kings County* was partitioned from the West Riding of York Shire, containing the six old Dutch towns on southwestern Long Island, as one of the "original twelve counties".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] This tract of land was recognized as a political entity for the first time, and the municipal groundwork was laid for a later expansive idea of a Brooklyn identity.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Lacking the patroon and tenant farmer system established along the Hudson River Valley, this agricultural county unusually came to have one of the highest percentages of slaves among the population in the "Original Thirteen Colonies" along the Atlantic Ocean eastern coast of North America.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] On August 27, 1776, the Battle of Long Island (also known as the 'Battle of Brooklyn') was fought, the first major engagement fought in the American Revolutionary War after independence was declared, and the largest of the entire conflict.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] British troops forced the Continental Army under George Washington off the heights near the modern sites of Green-Wood Cemetery, Prospect Park, and Grand Army Plaza.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Washington, viewing particularly fierce fighting at the Gowanus Creek and Old Stone House from atop a hill near the west end of present-day Atlantic Avenue, was reported to have emotionally exclaimed: "What brave men I must this day lose!".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The fortified American positions at Brooklyn Heights consequently became untenable and were evacuated a few days later, leaving the British in control of New York Harbor.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] While Washington's defeat on the battlefield cast early doubts on his ability as the commander, the tactical withdrawal of all his troops and supplies across the East River in a single night is now seen by historians as one of his most brilliant triumphs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The British controlled the surrounding region for the duration of the war, as New York City was soon occupied and became their military and political base of operations in British-held North America for the remainder of the conflict.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The British set up a system of prison ships off the coast of Brooklyn in Wallabout Bay.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] More American prisoners of war died on these prison ships than were killed in action on all the battlefield engagements of the war combined.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] One result of the Treaty of Paris in 1783 was the evacuation of the British from New York City, which was celebrated by New Yorkers into the 20th century.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The first half of the 19th century saw the beginning of the development of urban areas on the economically strategic East River shore of Kings County, facing the adolescent City of New York confined to Manhattan Island.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The New York Navy Yard operated in Wallabout Bay (border between Fort Greene and Williamsburg) during the 19th century and two-thirds of the 20th century.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The first center of urbanization sprang up in the Town of Brooklyn, directly across from Lower Manhattan, which saw the incorporation of the Village of Brooklyn in 1816.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Reliable steam ferry service across the East River to Fulton Landing converted Brooklyn Heights into a commuter town for Wall Street.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Ferry Road to Jamaica Pass became Fulton Street to East New York.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Town and Village were combined to form the first, kernel incarnation of the City of Brooklyn in 1834.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In a parallel development, the Town of Bushwick, farther up the river, saw the incorporation of the Village of Williamsburgh in 1827, which separated as the Town of Williamsburgh in 1840 and formed the short-lived City of Williamsburgh in 1851.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Industrial deconcentration in the mid-century was bringing shipbuilding and other manufacturing to the northern part of the county.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Each of the two cities and six towns in Kings County remained independent municipalities and purposely created non-aligning street grids with different naming systems.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] However, the East River shore was growing too fast for the three-year-old infant City of Williamsburg; it, along with its Town of Bushwick hinterland, was subsumed within a greater City of Brooklyn in 1855, subsequently dropping the 'h' from its name.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] By 1841, with the appearance of *The Brooklyn Eagle, and Kings County Democrat* published by Alfred G.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Stevens, the growing city across the East River from Manhattan was producing its own prominent newspaper.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] It later became the most popular and highest circulation afternoon paper in America.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Van Anden on April 19, 1842, and the paper was renamed *The Brooklyn Daily Eagle and Kings County Democrat* on June 1, 1846.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] On May 14, 1849, the name was shortened to *The Brooklyn Daily Eagle*; on September 5, 1938, it was further shortened to *Brooklyn Eagle*.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The establishment of the paper in the 1840s helped develop a separate identity for Brooklynites over the next century.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The borough's soon-to-be-famous National League baseball team, the Brooklyn Dodgers, also assisted with this.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Both major institutions were lost in the 1950s: the paper closed in 1955 after unsuccessful attempts at a sale following a reporters' strike, and the baseball team decamped for Los Angeles in a realignment of Major League Baseball in 1957.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Agitation against Southern slavery was stronger in Brooklyn than in New York, and under Republican leadership, the city was fervent in the Union cause in the Civil War.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] After the war the Henry Ward Beecher Monument was built downtown to honor a famous local abolitionist.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] A great victory arch was built at what was then the south end of town to celebrate the armed forces; this place is now called Grand Army Plaza.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The number of people living in Brooklyn grew rapidly early in the 19th century.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The city's population was 25,000 in 1834, but the police department comprised only 12 men on the day shift and another 12 on the night shift.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Every time a rash of burglaries broke out, officials blamed burglars from New York City.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Finally, in 1855, a modern police force was created, employing 150 men.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Voters complained of inadequate protection and excessive costs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In 1857, the state legislature merged the Brooklyn force with that of New York City.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Fervent in the Union cause, the city of Brooklyn played a major role in supplying troops and materiel for the American Civil War.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The best-known regiment to be sent off to war from the city was the 14th Brooklyn *"Red Legged Devils"*.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] They fought from 1861 to 1864, wore red the entire war, and were the only regiment named after a city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] President Abraham Lincoln called them into service, making them part of a handful of three-year enlisted soldiers in April 1861.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Unlike other regiments during the American Civil War, the 14th wore a uniform inspired by the French Chasseurs, a light infantry used for quick assaults.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] As a seaport and a manufacturing center, Brooklyn was well prepared to contribute to the Union's strengths in shipping and manufacturing.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The two combined in shipbuilding; the ironclad *Monitor* was built in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn is referred to as the twin city of New York in the 1883 poem, "The New Colossus" by Emma Lazarus, which appears on a plaque inside the Statue of Liberty.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The poem calls New York Harbor "the air-bridged harbor that twin cities frame".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] As a twin city to New York, it played a role in national affairs that was later overshadowed by decades of subordination by its old partner and rival.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Contiguous to the Heights, the less exclusive South Brooklyn was home to longtime civic leader James S.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Stranahan, who became known (often derisively) as the "Baron Haussmann of Brooklyn" for championing Prospect Park and other public works.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Economic growth continued, propelled by immigration and industrialization, and Brooklyn established itself as the third-most populous American city for much of the 19th century.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The waterfront from Gowanus to Greenpoint was developed with piers and factories.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Industrial access to the waterfront was improved by the Gowanus Canal and the canalized Newtown Creek.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] USS *Monitor* was the most famous product of the large and growing shipbuilding industry of Williamsburg.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] By century's end, Dean Alvord's Prospect Park South development (adjacent to the village of Flatbush) would serve as the template for contemporaneous "Victorian Flatbush" micro-neighborhoods and the post-consolidation emergence of outlying districts, such as Midwood and Marine Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Along with Oak Park, Illinois, it also presaged the automobile and commuter rail-driven vogue for more remote prewar suburban communities, such as Garden City, New York and Montclair, New Jersey.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The rapidly growing population needed more water, so the City built centralized waterworks, including the Ridgewood Reservoir.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The municipal Police Department, however, was abolished in 1854 in favor of a Metropolitan force covering also New York and Westchester Counties.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In 1865 the Brooklyn Fire Department (BFD) also gave way to the new Metropolitan Fire District.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Throughout this period the peripheral towns of Kings County, far from Manhattan and even from urban Brooklyn, maintained their rustic independence.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The only municipal change seen was the secession of the eastern section of the Town of Flatbush as the Town of New Lots in 1852.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The building of rail links such as the Brighton Beach Line in 1878 heralded the end of this isolation.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The Brooklyn Bridegrooms played professional baseball at Washington Park in the convenient suburb of Park Slope and elsewhere.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Early in the next century, under their new name of Brooklyn Dodgers, they brought baseball to Ebbets Field, beyond Prospect Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Racetracks, amusement parks, and beach resorts opened in Brighton Beach, Coney Island, and elsewhere in the southern part of the county.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Toward the end of the 19th century, the City of Brooklyn experienced its final, explosive growth spurt.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Park Slope was rapidly urbanized, with its eastern summit soon emerging as the city's third "Gold Coast" district alongside Brooklyn Heights and The Hill; notable residents of the era included American Chicle Company co-founder Thomas Adams Jr. and New York Central Railroad executive Clinton L.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] East of The Hill, Bedford-Stuyvesant coalesced as an upper middle class enclave for lawyers, shopkeepers, and merchants of German and Irish descent (notably exemplified by John C.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Kelley, a water meter magnate and close friend of President Grover Cleveland), with nearby Crown Heights gradually fulfilling an analogous role for the city's Jewish population as development continued through the early 20th century.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Northeast of Bedford-Stuyvesant, Bushwick (by now a working class, predominantly German district) established a considerable brewery industry; the so-called "Brewer's Row" encompassed 14 breweries operating in a 14-block area in 1890.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] On the southwestern waterfront of Kings County, railroads and industrialization spread to Sunset Park (then coterminous with the city's sprawling, sparsely populated Eighth Ward) and adjacent Bay Ridge (hitherto a resort-like subsection of the Town of New Utrecht).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Within a decade, the city had annexed the Town of New Lots in 1886; the Towns of Flatbush, Gravesend and New Utrecht in 1894; and the Town of Flatlands in 1896.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn had reached its natural municipal boundaries at the ends of Kings County.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn elected a mayor from 1834 until 1898, after which it was consolidated into the City of Greater New York, the second mayor of which (1902–1903), Seth Low, had been Mayor of Brooklyn from 1882 to 1885.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Since 1898, Brooklyn has, in place of a separate mayor, elected a Borough President.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In 1883, the Brooklyn Bridge was completed, transportation to Manhattan was no longer by water only, and the City of Brooklyn's ties to the City of New York were strengthened.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Andrew Haswell Green and other progressives said yes, and eventually, they prevailed against the *Daily Eagle* and other conservative forces.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In 1894, residents of Brooklyn and the other counties voted by a slight majority to merge, effective in 1898.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Kings County retained its status as one of New York State's counties, but the loss of Brooklyn's separate identity as a city was met with consternation by some residents at the time.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Many newspapers of the day called the merger the "Great Mistake of 1898".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn is 97 square miles (250 km2) in area, of which 71 square miles (180 km2) is land (73%), and 26 square miles (67 km2) is water (27%); the borough is the second-largest by land area among the New York City's boroughs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] However, Kings County, coterminous with Brooklyn, is New York State's fourth-smallest county by land area and third-smallest by total area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn lies at the southwestern end of Long Island, and the borough's western border constitutes the island's western tip.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] To the east of Brooklyn lies the borough of Queens, which contains John F.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Kennedy International Airport in that borough's Jamaica neighborhood, approximately two miles from the border of Brooklyn's East New York neighborhood.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Under the Köppen climate classification, Brooklyn experiences a humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*), with partial shielding from the Appalachian Mountains and moderating influences from the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn receives plentiful precipitation all year round, with nearly 50 in (1,300 mm) yearly.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Snowfall is most common in February with around 20–21 centimeters or 8.3–8.5 inches.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The area averages 234 days with at least some sunshine annually, and averages 57% of possible sunshine annually, accumulating 2,535 hours of sunshine per annum.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn lies in the USDA plant hardiness zone 7b.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn's neighborhoods are dynamic in ethnic composition.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] For example, the early to mid-20th century, Brownsville had a majority of Jewish residents; since the 1970s it has been majority African American.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Midwood during the early 20th century was filled with ethnic Irish, then filled with Jewish residents for nearly 50 years, and is slowly becoming a Pakistani enclave.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn's most populous racial group, white, declined from 97.2% in 1930 to 46.9% by 1990.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The borough attracts people previously living in other cities in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Of these, most come from Chicago, Detroit, San Francisco, Washington, D.C., Baltimore, Philadelphia, Boston, Cincinnati, and Seattle.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In 2010, 51.6% of the population was counted as members of religious congregations.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In 2014, there were 914 religious organizations in Brooklyn, the 10th most of all counties in the nation.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn contains dozens of distinct neighborhoods representing many of the major culturally identified groups found within New York City.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Over 600,000 Jews, particularly Orthodox and Hasidic Jews, have become concentrated in such historically Jewish areas as Borough Park, Williamsburg, and Midwood, where there are many yeshivas, synagogues, and kosher restaurants, as well as a variety of Jewish businesses.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Other notable religious Jewish neighborhoods with a longstanding cultural lineage include Canarsie, Sea Gate, and Crown Heights, home to the Chabad world headquarters.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Neighborhoods with largely defunct yet historically notable Jewish populations include central Flatbush, East Flatbush, Brownsville, East New York, Bensonhurst and Sheepshead Bay (particularly its Madison subsection).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Many hospitals in Brooklyn were started by Jewish charities, including Maimonides Medical Center in Borough Park and Brookdale Hospital in East Flatbush.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] According to the American Jewish Population Project in 2020, Brooklyn was home to over 480,000 Jews.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In 2023, the UJA-Federation of New York estimated that Brooklyn is home to 462,000 Jews, a large decrease compared to the 561,000 estimated in 2011.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Many non-Orthodox Jews (ranging from observant members of various denominations to atheists of Jewish cultural heritage) are concentrated in Ditmas Park and Park Slope, with smaller observant and culturally Jewish populations in Brooklyn Heights, Cobble Hill, Brighton Beach, and Coney Island.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Over 200,000 Chinese Americans live throughout the southern parts of Brooklyn, primarily concentrated in Sunset Park, Bensonhurst, Gravesend, and Homecrest.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn is the borough that is home to the highest number of Chinatowns in New York City.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The largest concentration is in Sunset Park along 8th Avenue, which has become known for its Chinese culture since the opening of the now-defunct Winley Supermarket in 1986 spurred widespread settlement in the area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Many Chinese restaurants can be found throughout Sunset Park, and the area hosts a popular Chinese New Year celebration.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn's African American and Caribbean communities are spread throughout much of Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn's West Indian community is concentrated in the Crown Heights, Flatbush, East Flatbush, Kensington, and Canarsie neighborhoods in central Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn is home to the largest community of West Indians outside of the Caribbean.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Although the largest West Indian groups in Brooklyn are Jamaicans, Guyanese and Haitians, there are West Indian immigrants from nearly every part of the Caribbean.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Crown Heights and Flatbush are home to many of Brooklyn's West Indian restaurants and bakeries.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn has an annual, celebrated Carnival in the tradition of pre-Lenten celebrations in the islands.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Started by natives of Trinidad and Tobago, the West Indian Labor Day Parade takes place every Labor Day on Eastern Parkway.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The Brooklyn Academy of Music also holds the DanceAfrica festival in late May, featuring street vendors and dance performances showcasing food and culture from all parts of Africa.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Since the opening of the IND Fulton Street Line in 1936, Bedford-Stuyvesant has been home to one of the most famous African American communities in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Working-class communities remain prevalent in Brownsville, East New York and Coney Island, while remnants of similar communities in Prospect Heights, Fort Greene and Clinton Hill have endured amid widespread gentrification.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The borough's Hispanic population diversified after the 1965 Hart-Cellar Act loosened restrictions on immigration from elsewhere in Latin America.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Bushwick has since emerged as the largest hub of Brooklyn's Hispanic American community.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Like other Hispanic neighborhoods in New York City, Bushwick has an established Puerto Rican presence, along with an influx of many Dominicans, South Americans, Central Americans and Mexicans.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] As nearly 80% of Bushwick's population is Hispanic, its residents have created many businesses to support their various national and distinct traditions in food and other items.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Sunset Park's population is 42% Hispanic, made up of these various ethnic groups.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn's main Hispanic groups are Puerto Ricans, Mexicans, Dominicans and Ecuadorians; they are spread out throughout the borough.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Puerto Ricans and Dominicans are predominant in Bushwick, Williamsburg's South Side and East New York.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Mexicans (especially from the state of Puebla) now predominate alongside Chinese immigrants in Sunset Park, although remnants of the neighborhood's once-substantial postwar Puerto Rican and Dominican communities continue to reside below 39th Street.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] A Panamanian enclave exists in Crown Heights.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn is also home to many Russians and Ukrainians, who are mainly concentrated in the areas of Brighton Beach and Sheepshead Bay.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brighton Beach features many Russian and Ukrainian businesses and has been nicknamed *Little Russia* and *Little Odessa*, respectively.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In the 1970s, Soviet Jews won the right to immigrate, and many ended up in Brighton Beach.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In recent years, the non-Jewish Russian and Ukrainian communities of Brighton Beach have grown, and the area is now home to a diverse collection of immigrants from across the former USSR.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Smaller concentrations of Russian and Ukrainian Americans are scattered elsewhere in south Brooklyn, including Bay Ridge, Bensonhurst, Homecrest, Coney Island, and Mill Basin.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] A growing community of Uzbek Americans have settled alongside them in recent years due to their ability to speak Russian.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn's Polish inhabitants are historically concentrated in Greenpoint, home to Little Poland.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Other longstanding settlements in Borough Park and Sunset Park have endured, while more recent immigrants are scattered throughout the southern parts of Brooklyn alongside the Russian and Ukrainian American communities.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Despite widespread migration to Staten Island and more suburban areas in metropolitan New York throughout the postwar era, notable concentrations of Italian Americans continue to reside in the neighborhoods of Bensonhurst, Dyker Heights, Bay Ridge, Bath Beach and Gravesend.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] All of the aforementioned neighborhoods have retained Italian restaurants, bakeries, delicatessens, pizzerias, cafes and social clubs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] In the early 20th century, many Lebanese and Syrian Christians settled around Atlantic Avenue west of Flatbush Avenue in Boerum Hill; more recently, this area has evolved into a Yemeni commercial district.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brighton Beach is home to a growing Pakistani American community, while Midwood is home to *Little Pakistan* along Coney Island Avenue (recently co-named Muhammad Ali Jinnah Way).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Pakistani Independence Day is celebrated every year with parades and parties on Coney Island Avenue.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Just to the north, Kensington is one of New York's several emerging Bangladeshi enclaves.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Third-, fourth- and fifth-generation Irish Americans can be found throughout Brooklyn, with moderate concentrations enduring in the neighborhoods of Windsor Terrace, Park Slope, Bay Ridge, Marine Park and Gerritsen Beach.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Historical communities also existed in Vinegar Hill and other waterfront industrial neighborhoods, such as Greenpoint and Sunset Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Paralleling the Italian American community, many moved to Staten Island and suburban areas in the postwar era.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] While not as extensive as the Indian American population in Queens, younger professionals of Asian Indian origin are finding Brooklyn to be a convenient alternative to Manhattan to find housing.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] According to the 2020 Census, nearly 40,000 Indian Americans call Brooklyn home.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brighton Beach is home to a growing Pakistani American community, while Midwood is home to Little Pakistan along Coney Island Avenue recently renamed Muhammad Ali Jinnah way.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Pakistan Independence Day is celebrated every year with parades and parties on Coney Island Avenue.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn's Greek Americans live throughout the borough.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] A historical concentration has endured in Bay Ridge and adjacent areas, where there is a noticeable cluster of Hellenic-focused schools, businesses and cultural institutions.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Other businesses are situated in Downtown Brooklyn near Atlantic Avenue.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] As in much of the New York metropolitan area, Greek-owned diners are found throughout the borough.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn is home to a large and growing number of same-sex couples.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Same-sex marriages in New York were legalized on June 24, 2011, and were authorized to take place beginning 30 days thereafter.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] The Park Slope neighborhood spearheaded the popularity of Brooklyn among lesbians, and Prospect Heights has an LGBT residential presence.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Numerous neighborhoods have since become home to LGBT communities.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn Liberation March, the largest transgender-rights demonstration in LGBTQ history, took place on June 14, 2020, stretching from Grand Army Plaza to Fort Greene, focused on supporting Black transgender lives, drawing an estimated 15,000 to 20,000 participants.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Brooklyn became a preferred site for artists and hipsters to set up live/work spaces after being priced out of the same types of living arrangements in Manhattan.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] Various neighborhoods in Brooklyn, including Williamsburg, DUMBO, Red Hook, and Park Slope evolved as popular neighborhoods for artists-in-residence.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p01] However, rents and costs of living have since increased dramatically in these same neighborhoods, forcing artists to move to somewhat less expensive neighborhoods in Brooklyn or across Upper New York Bay to locales in New Jersey, such as Jersey City or Hoboken.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] At the 2020 census, 2,736,074 people lived in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The United States Census Bureau had estimated Brooklyn's population increased by 2.2% to 2,559,903 between 2010 and 2019.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn's estimated population represented 30.7% of New York City's estimated population of 8,336,817; 33.5% of Long Island's population of 7,701,172; and 13.2% of New York State's population of 19,542,209.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 2020, the government of New York City projected Brooklyn's population at 2,648,403.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The 2019 census estimates determined there were 958,567 households with an average of 2.66 persons per household.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] There were 1,065,399 housing units in 2019 and a median gross rent of $1,426.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Citing growth, Brooklyn gained 9,696 building permits at the 2019 census estimates program.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Hispanics and Latinos made up 18.9% of Brooklyn's population.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 2010, Brooklyn had some neighborhoods segregated based on race, ethnicity, and religion.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Overall, the southwest half of Brooklyn is racially mixed although it contains few black residents; the northeast section is mostly black and Hispanic/Latino.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn has a high degree of linguistic diversity.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In total, 45.9% (1,051,456) of Brooklyn's population ages 5 and older spoke a home language other than English.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn has played a major role in various aspects of American culture, including literature, cinema, and theater.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn's accent has often been portrayed as the "typical New Yorker accent" in American media, although this accent and its stereotypes are supposedly diminishing in currency.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn's official colors are blue and gold.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn hosts the world-renowned Brooklyn Academy of Music, the Brooklyn Philharmonic, and the second-largest public art collection in the United States, housed in the Brooklyn Museum.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Brooklyn Museum, opened in 1897, is New York City's second-largest public art museum.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] It has in its permanent collection more than 1.5 million objects, from ancient Egyptian masterpieces to contemporary art.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Brooklyn Children's Museum, the world's first museum dedicated to children, opened in December 1899.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The only such New York State institution accredited by the American Alliance of Museums, it is one of the few globally to have a permanent collection – over 30,000 cultural objects and natural history specimens.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Brooklyn Academy of Music (BAM) includes a 2,109-seat opera house, an 874-seat theater, and the art-house BAM Rose Cinemas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Ann's Warehouse are on the other side of Downtown Brooklyn in the DUMBO arts district.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn Technical High School has the second-largest auditorium in New York City (after Radio City Music Hall), with a seating capacity of over 3,000.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn has several local newspapers: The *Brooklyn Daily Eagle*, *Bay Currents* (Oceanfront Brooklyn), *Brooklyn View*, *The Brooklyn Paper*, and Courier-Life Publications.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Courier-Life Publications, owned by Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation, is Brooklyn's largest chain of newspapers.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn is also served by the major New York dailies, including *The New York Times*, the *New York Daily News*, and the *New York Post*.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Several others are now defunct, including the *Brooklyn Union* (1867–1937), and the *Brooklyn Times*.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The borough is home to the arts and politics monthly *Brooklyn Rail*, as well as the arts and cultural quarterly *Cabinet*.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] *Hello Mr.* is also published in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] *El Diario La Prensa*, the largest and oldest Spanish-language daily newspaper in the United States, maintains its corporate headquarters at 1 MetroTech Center in Downtown Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Major ethnic publications include the Brooklyn–Queens Catholic paper *The Tablet*, *Hamodia*, an Orthodox Jewish daily, and *The Jewish Press*, an Orthodox Jewish weekly.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Many nationally distributed ethnic newspapers are based in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Over 60 ethnic groups, writing in 42 languages, publish some 300 non-English language magazines and newspapers in New York City.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Among them is the quarterly *L'Idea*, a bilingual magazine printed in Italian and English since 1974.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In addition, many newspapers published abroad, such as *The Daily Gleaner* and *The Star* of Jamaica, are available in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] *Our Time Press*, published weekly by DBG Media, covers the Village of Brooklyn with a motto of "The Local Paper with the Global View".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The City of New York has an official television station, run by NYC Media, which features programming based in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn Community Access Television is the borough's public access channel.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Its studios are at the BRIC Arts Media venue, called BRIC House, located on Fulton Street in the Fort Greene section of the borough.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn's job market is driven by three main factors: the performance of the national and city economy, population flows and the borough's position as a convenient back office for New York's businesses.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Forty-four percent of Brooklyn's employed population, or 410,000 people, work in the borough; more than half of the borough's residents work outside its boundaries.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] As a result, economic conditions in Manhattan are important to the borough's jobseekers.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Strong international immigration to Brooklyn generates jobs in services, retailing and construction.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Jobs in the borough were traditionally concentrated in manufacturing, but since 1975, Brooklyn has shifted from a manufacturing-based to a service-based economy.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 2004, 215,000 Brooklyn residents worked in the services sector, while 27,500 worked in manufacturing.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Although manufacturing has declined, a substantial base has remained in apparel and niche manufacturing concerns such as furniture, fabricated metals, and food products.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The pharmaceutical company Pfizer was founded in Brooklyn in 1869 and had a manufacturing plant in the borough for many years that employed thousands of workers, but the plant shut down in 2008.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] However, new light-manufacturing concerns in packaging organic and high-end food have sprung up in the old plant.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Established as a shipbuilding facility in 1801, the Brooklyn Navy Yard employed 70,000 people at its peak during World War II and was then the largest employer in the borough.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The *Missouri*, the ship on which the Japanese formally surrendered, was built there, as was the *Maine*, whose sinking off Havana led to the start of the Spanish–American War.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The iron-sided Civil War vessel the *Monitor* was built in Greenpoint.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] From 1968 to 1979 Seatrain Shipbuilding was the major employer.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Later tenants include industrial design firms, food processing businesses, artisans, and the film and television production industry.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] About 230 private-sector firms providing 4,000 jobs are at the Yard.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Construction and services are the fastest-growing sectors.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Most employers in Brooklyn are small businesses.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 2000, 91% of the approximately 38,704 business establishments in Brooklyn had fewer than 20 employees.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] As of August 2008, the borough's unemployment rate was 5.9%.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn is also home to many banks and credit unions.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] According to the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation, there were 37 banks and 26 credit unions operating in the borough in 2010.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The rezoning of Downtown Brooklyn has generated over US$10 billion of private investment and $300 million in public improvements since 2004.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn is also attracting numerous high technology start-up companies, as Silicon Alley, the metonym for New York City's entrepreneurship ecosystem, has expanded from Lower Manhattan into Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn's major professional sports team is the NBA's Brooklyn Nets.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Nets moved into the borough in 2012, and play their home games at Barclays Center in Prospect Heights.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Previously, the Nets had played in Uniondale, New York and in New Jersey.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In April 2020, the New York Liberty of the WNBA were sold to the Nets' owners and moved their home venue from Madison Square Garden to the Barclays Center.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Barclays Center was also the home arena for the NHL's New York Islanders full-time from 2015 to 2018, then part-time from 2018 to 2020 (alternating with Nassau Coliseum in Uniondale).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Islanders had originally played at Nassau Coliseum full-time since their inception until 2015 when their lease at the venue expired and the team moved to Barclays Center.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 2020, the team returned to Nassau Coliseum full-time for one season before moving to the UBS Arena in Elmont, New York in 2021.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn also has a storied sports history.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] It has been home to many famous sports figures such as Joe Paterno, Vince Lombardi, Mike Tyson, Zab Judah, Joe Torre, Sandy Koufax, Billy Cunningham and Vitas Gerulaitis.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Basketball legend Michael Jordan was born in Brooklyn though he grew up in Wilmington, North Carolina.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In the earliest days of organized baseball, Brooklyn teams dominated the new game.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The second recorded game of baseball was played near what is now Fort Greene Park on October 24, 1845.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn's Excelsiors, Atlantics and Eckfords were the leading teams from the mid-1850s through the Civil War, and there were dozens of local teams with neighborhood league play, such as at Mapleton Oval.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn's most famous historical team, the Brooklyn Dodgers, named for "trolley dodgers" played at Ebbets Field.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 1947 Jackie Robinson was hired by the Dodgers as the first African-American player in Major League Baseball in the modern era.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 1955, the Dodgers, perennial National League pennant winners, won the only World Series for Brooklyn against their rival New York Yankees.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The event was marked by mass euphoria and celebrations.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Just two years later, the Dodgers moved to Los Angeles.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Walter O'Malley, the team's owner at the time, is still vilified, even by Brooklynites too young to remember the Dodgers as Brooklyn's ball club.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] After a 43-year hiatus, professional baseball returned to the borough in 2001 with the Brooklyn Cyclones, a minor league team that plays in MCU Park in Coney Island.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] They are an affiliate of the New York Mets.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The minor-league New York Cosmos soccer club played its home games at MCU Park in 2017.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] A new Brooklyn FC will begin play in 2024, fielding a women's team in the first-division USL Super League and a men's team in the second-division USL Championship beginning in 2025.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn once had a National Football League team named the Brooklyn Lions in 1926, who played at Ebbets Field.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In rugby union, Rugby United New York joined Major League Rugby in 2019 and played their home games at MCU Park through the 2021 season.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn has one of the most active recreational fishing fleets in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In addition to a large private fleet along Jamaica Bay, there is a substantial public fleet within Sheepshead Bay.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Species caught include Black Fish, Porgy, Striped Bass, Black Sea Bass, Fluke, and Flounder.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Each of New York City's five counties, coterminous with each borough, has its own criminal court system and District Attorney, the chief public prosecutor who is directly elected by popular vote.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn has 16 City Council members, the largest number of any of the five boroughs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Brooklyn Borough Government includes a borough president and a court, library, borough government board, head of borough government, deputy head of borough government and deputy borough government president.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn has 18 of the city's 59 community districts, each served by an unpaid community board with advisory powers under the city's Uniform Land Use Review Procedure.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Each board has a paid district manager who acts as an interlocutor with city agencies.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Kings County Democratic County Committee (aka the Brooklyn Democratic Party) is the county committee of the Democratic Party in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The United States Postal Service operates post offices in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Brooklyn Main Post Office is located at 271 Cadman Plaza East in Downtown Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn has been a bastion of left-wing politics since before the turn of the 20th century; with its concentration of workers and immigrants, several socialist and labor parties have found purchase in the borough.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In the municipal and state elections of 1917, New York City elected ten assemblymen and seven aldermen of the Socialist Party; three of the assemblymen and two of the aldermen were from Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 1941, shortly before American entry into World War II, Brooklyn elected communist Peter V.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Cacchione to the City Council, making him the first open member of the Communist Party elected to public office in the state.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Following the 2025 New York City mayoral primary and general election, several neighborhoods in the borough have been identified as part of the so-called "Commie corridor," a region of the city strongly supportive of Zohran Mamdani and other Democratic Socialists.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] As is the case with sister boroughs Manhattan and the Bronx, Brooklyn has not voted for a Republican in a national presidential election since Calvin Coolidge in 1924.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In the 2008 presidential election, Democrat Barack Obama received 79.4% of the vote in Brooklyn while Republican John McCain received 20.0%.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 2012, Barack Obama increased his Democratic margin of victory in the borough, dominating Brooklyn with 82.0% of the vote to Republican Mitt Romney's 16.9%.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 2024, Republican Donald Trump reached 27% of the vote, and held Kamala Harris at just over 70%, a significant shift from Joe Biden's performance of over 76% in 2020.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] While still a decisive Democratic victory, this was the strongest Republican support in Brooklyn since 1988, and the largest number of raw Republican votes there since 1972.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] As of 2023, four Democrats and one Republican represented Brooklyn in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] One congressional district lies entirely within the borough.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn offers a wide array of private housing, as well as public housing, which is administered by the New York City Housing Authority (NYCHA).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Affordable rental and co-operative housing units throughout the borough were created under the Mitchell–Lama Housing Program.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] There were 1,101,441 housing units in 2022 at an average density of 15,876 units per square mile (6,130/km2).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Public housing administered by NYCHA accounts for more than 100,000 residents in nearly 50,000 units in 2023.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Education in Brooklyn is provided by a vast number of public and private institutions.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Non-charter public schools in the borough are managed by the New York City Department of Education, the largest public school system in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn Technical High School, commonly called Brooklyn Tech, a New York City public high school, is the largest specialized high school for science, mathematics, and technology in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn Tech is across the street from Fort Greene Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] This high school was built from 1930 to 1933 at a cost of about $6 million and is 12 stories high.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn Tech is noted for its famous alumni (including two Nobel Laureates), its academics, and a large number of graduates attending prestigious universities.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn College is a senior college of the City University of New York (CUNY), and was the first public coeducational liberal arts college in New York City.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The college ranked in the top 10 nationally for the second consecutive year in Princeton Review's 2006 guidebook, *America's Best Value Colleges*.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Many of its students are first and second-generation Americans.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Founded in 1970, Medgar Evers College is a senior college of the City University of New York.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The college offers programs at the baccalaureate and associate degree levels, as well as adult and continuing education classes for central Brooklyn residents, corporations, government agencies, and community organizations.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Medgar Evers College is a few blocks east of Prospect Park in Crown Heights.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] CUNY's New York City College of Technology (City Tech) of The City University of New York (Downtown Brooklyn/Brooklyn Heights) is the largest public college of technology in New York State and a national model for technological education.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Established in 1946, City Tech can trace its roots to 1881 when the Technical Schools of the Metropolitan Museum of Art were renamed the New York Trade School.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] That institution—which became the Voorhees Technical Institute many decades later—was soon a model for the development of technical and vocational schools worldwide.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 1971, Voorhees was incorporated into City Tech.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] SUNY Downstate College of Medicine, founded as the Long Island College Hospital in 1860, is the oldest hospital-based medical school in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Medical Center comprises the College of Medicine, College of Health Related Professions, College of Nursing, School of Public Health, School of Graduate Studies, and University Hospital of Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Half of the Medical Center's students are minorities or immigrants.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The College of Medicine has the highest percentage of minority students of any medical school in New York State.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Adelphi University, based in Garden City, moved its Manhattan Campus in 2023 to a new location on Livingston Street in Downtown Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The move marks a return to Brooklyn for the university, which originated on Adelphi Street with the Adelphi Academy.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Francis College, which has created a new campus at 179 Livingston Street.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn Law School was founded in 1901 and is notable for its diverse student body.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Women and African Americans were enrolled in 1909.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] According to the Leiter Report, a compendium of law school rankings published by Brian Leiter, Brooklyn Law School places 31st nationally for the quality of students.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Long Island University is a private university headquartered in Brookville on Long Island, with a campus in Downtown Brooklyn with 6,417 undergraduate students.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Brooklyn campus has strong science and medical technology programs, at the graduate and undergraduate levels.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Pratt Institute, in Clinton Hill, is a private college founded in 1887 with programs in engineering, architecture, and the arts.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Some buildings in the school's Brooklyn campus are official landmarks.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Pratt has over 4700 students, with most at its Brooklyn campus.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Graduate programs include a library and information science, architecture, and urban planning.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Undergraduate programs include architecture, construction management, writing, critical and visual studies, industrial design and fine arts, totaling over 25 programs in all.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The New York University Tandon School of Engineering, the United States' second oldest private institute of technology, founded in 1854, has its main campus in Downtown's MetroTech Center, a commercial, civic and educational redevelopment project of which it was a key sponsor.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] NYU-Tandon is one of the 18 schools and colleges that comprise New York University (NYU).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Francis College is a Catholic college in Downtown Brooklyn founded in 1859 by Franciscan friars.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Over 2,400 students attend the small liberal arts college.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Francis is considered by *The New York Times* as one of the more diverse colleges, and was ranked one of the best baccalaureate colleges by *Forbes* magazine and *U.S.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn also has smaller liberal arts institutions, such as Saint Joseph's College in Clinton Hill and Boricua College in Williamsburg.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Kingsborough Community College is a junior college in the City University of New York system in Manhattan Beach.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] New York City College of Technology (City Tech) is a public college in New York City.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Founded in 1946, it is the City University of New York's college of technology.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Its main urban campus is located in Downtown Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] As an independent system, separate from the New York and Queens public library systems, the Brooklyn Public Library offers thousands of public programs, millions of books, and use of more than 850 free Internet-accessible computers.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] It also has books and periodicals in all the major languages spoken in Brooklyn, including English, Russian, Chinese, Spanish, Hebrew, and Haitian Creole, as well as French, Yiddish, Hindi, Bengali, Polish, Italian, and Arabic.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Central Library is a landmarked building facing Grand Army Plaza.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] There are 58 library branches, placing one within a half-mile of each Brooklyn resident.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] It will provide access and training to arts applications and technologies not widely available to the public.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The collections will include the subjects of art, theater, dance, music, film, photography, and architecture.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] A special archive will house the records and history of Brooklyn's arts communities.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In 2015, about 57 percent of all households in Brooklyn were households without automobiles.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The citywide rate is 55 percent in New York City.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn features extensive public transit.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Nineteen New York City Subway services, including the Franklin Avenue Shuttle, traverse the borough.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Approximately 92.8% of Brooklyn residents traveling to Manhattan use the subway, despite the fact some neighborhoods like Flatlands and Marine Park are poorly served by subway service.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Proposed New York City Subway lines never built include a line along Nostrand or Utica Avenues to Marine Park, as well as a subway line to Spring Creek.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn was once served by an extensive network of streetcars, but many were replaced by the public bus network that covers the entire borough.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] There is also daily express bus service into Manhattan.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] New York's famous yellow cabs also provide transportation in Brooklyn, although they are less numerous in the borough.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] There are three commuter rail stations in Brooklyn: East New York, Nostrand Avenue, and Atlantic Terminal, the terminus of the Atlantic Branch of the Long Island Rail Road.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The terminal is near the Atlantic Avenue–Barclays Center subway station, with ten connecting subway services.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In February 2015, Mayor Bill de Blasio announced that the city government would begin a citywide ferry service called NYC Ferry to extend ferry transportation to communities in the city that have been traditionally underserved by public transit.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The ferry opened in May 2017, with the Bay Ridge ferry serving southwestern Brooklyn and the East River Ferry serving northwestern Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] A third route, the Rockaway ferry, makes one stop in the borough at Brooklyn Army Terminal.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] A streetcar line, the Brooklyn–Queens Connector, was proposed by the city in February 2016, with the planned timeline calling for service to begin around 2024.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Other prominent roadways are the Prospect Expressway (New York State Route 27), the Belt Parkway, and the Jackie Robinson Parkway (formerly the Interborough Parkway).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Planned expressways that were never built include the Bushwick Expressway, an extension of I-78 and the Cross-Brooklyn Expressway, I-878.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Major thoroughfares include Atlantic Avenue, Fourth Avenue, 86th Street, Kings Highway, Bay Parkway, Ocean Parkway, Eastern Parkway, Linden Boulevard, McGuinness Boulevard, Flatbush Avenue, Pennsylvania Avenue, and Nostrand Avenue.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Much of Brooklyn has only named streets, but Park Slope, Bay Ridge, Sunset Park, Bensonhurst, and Borough Park and the other western sections have numbered streets running approximately northwest to southeast, and numbered avenues going approximately northeast to southwest.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] East of Dahill Road, lettered avenues (like Avenue M) run east and west, and numbered streets have the prefix "East".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] South of Avenue O, related numbered streets west of Dahill Road use the "West" designation.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] This set of numbered streets ranges from West 37th Street to East 108 Street, and the avenues range from A–Z with names substituted for some of them in some neighborhoods (notably Albemarle, Beverley, Cortelyou, Dorchester, Ditmas, Foster, Farragut, Glenwood, Quentin).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Numbered streets prefixed by "North" and "South" in Williamsburg, and "Bay", "Beach", "Brighton", "Plumb", "Paerdegat" or "Flatlands" along the southern and southwestern waterfront are loosely based on the old grids of the original towns of Kings County that eventually consolidated to form Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] These names often reflect the bodies of water or beaches around them, such as Plumb Beach or Paerdegat Basin.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn is connected to Manhattan by three bridges, the Brooklyn, Manhattan, and Williamsburg Bridge; a vehicular tunnel, the Brooklyn–Battery Tunnel (also known as the Hugh L.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Carey Tunnel); and several subway tunnels.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Verrazzano–Narrows Bridge links Brooklyn with the more suburban borough of Staten Island.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Brooklyn was long a major shipping port, especially at the Brooklyn Army Terminal and Bush Terminal in Sunset Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Most container ship cargo operations have shifted to the New Jersey side of New York Harbor, while the Brooklyn Cruise Terminal in Red Hook is a focal point for New York's growing cruise industry.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The *Queen Mary 2*, one of the world's largest ocean liners, was designed specifically to fit under the Verrazzano–Narrows Bridge, the longest suspension bridge in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] She makes regular ports of call at the Red Hook terminal on her transatlantic crossings from Southampton, England.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The Brooklyn waterfront formerly employed tens of thousands of borough residents and acted as an incubator for industries across the entire city, and the decline of the port exacerbated Brooklyn's decline in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] In February 2015, Mayor Bill de Blasio announced that the city government would begin NYC Ferry to extend ferry transportation to traditionally underserved communities in the city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The ferry opened in May 2017, offering commuter services from the western shore of Brooklyn to Manhattan via three routes.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The East River Ferry serves points in Lower Manhattan, Midtown, Long Island City, and northwestern Brooklyn via its East River route.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] The South Brooklyn and Rockaway routes serve southwestern Brooklyn before terminating in lower Manhattan.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] Ferries to Coney Island are also planned.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] SeaStreak also offers a weekday ferry service between the Brooklyn Army Terminal and the Manhattan ferry slips at Pier 11/Wall Street downtown and East 34th Street Ferry Landing in midtown.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/brooklyn-new-york-p02] A Cross-Harbor Rail Tunnel, originally proposed in the 1920s as a core project for the then-new Port Authority of New York is again being studied and discussed as a way to ease freight movements across a large swath of the metropolitan area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Both Dallas and Fort Worth were initially developed as a product of the construction of major railroad lines through the area allowing access to cotton, cattle, and later oil in North and East Texas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The construction of the Interstate Highway System reinforced Dallas's prominence as a transportation hub, with four major interstate highways converging in the city and a fifth interstate loop around it.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas then developed as a strong industrial and financial center and a major inland port, due to the convergence of major railroad lines, interstate highways, and the construction of Dallas Fort Worth International Airport, one of the largest and busiest airports in the world.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In addition, Dallas Area Rapid Transit (DART) operates rail and bus transit services throughout the city and its surrounding suburbs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dominant sectors of its diverse economy include defense, financial services (such as traditional banking, investment banking, private equity, and venture capital), information technology, telecommunications, and transportation.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex hosts 23 *Fortune* 500 companies, the second-most in Texas and fourth-most in the United States, and 11 of those companies are located within Dallas city limits.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Over 41 colleges and universities are located within its metropolitan area, which is the most of any metropolitan area in Texas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The city has a population from a myriad of ethnic and religious backgrounds.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Indigenous tribes in North Texas included the Caddo, Tawakoni, Wichita, Kickapoo and Comanche.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Spanish colonists claimed the territory of Texas in the 18th century as a part of the Viceroyalty of New Spain.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Later, France also claimed the area but never established much settlement.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In all, six flags have flown over the area preceding and during the city's history: those of France, Spain, and Mexico, the flag of the Republic of Texas, the Confederate flag, and the flag of the United States of America.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 1819, the Adams–Onís Treaty between the United States and Spain defined the Red River as the northern boundary of New Spain, officially placing the future location of Dallas well within Spanish territory.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The area remained under Spanish rule until 1821, when Mexico declared independence from Spain, and the area was considered part of the Mexican state of Coahuila y Tejas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 1836, Texians, with a majority of Anglo-American settlers, gained independence from Mexico and formed the Republic of Texas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Three years after Texas achieved independence, John Neely Bryan surveyed the area around present-day Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 1839, accompanied by his dog and a Cherokee he called Ned, he planted a stake in the ground on a bluff located near three forks of the Trinity River and left.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Two years later, in 1841, he returned to establish a permanent settlement named Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The official historical marker states it was named after Vice President George M.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Other potential theories for the origin include his brother, Commodore Alexander James Dallas, as well as brothers Walter R.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] A further theory gives the ultimate origin as the village of Dallas, Moray, Scotland, similar to the way Houston, Texas, was named after Sam Houston, whose ancestors came from the Scottish village of Houston, Renfrewshire.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Republic of Texas was annexed by the United States in 1845 and Dallas County was established the following year.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas was formally incorporated as a city on February 2, 1856.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In the mid-1800s, a group of French Socialists established La Réunion, a short-lived community, along the Trinity River in what is now West Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] With the construction of railroads, Dallas became a business and trading center and was booming by the end of the 19th century.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] It became an industrial city, attracting workers from Texas, the South, and the Midwest.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Praetorian Building in Dallas of 15 stories, built in 1909, was among the first skyscrapers west of the Mississippi and the tallest building in Texas for some time.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] It marked the prominence of Dallas as a city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] A racetrack for thoroughbreds was built and their owners established the Dallas Jockey Club.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Trotters raced at a track in Fort Worth, where a similar drivers club was based.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The rapid expansion of population increased competition for jobs and housing.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 1910, a white mob of hundreds of people lynched a black man, Allen Brooks, accused of raping a little girl.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The mob tortured Brooks, then killed him at the downtown intersection of Main and Akard by hanging him from a decorative archway inscribed with the words "Welcome Visitors".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Thousands of Dallasites came to gawk at the torture scene, collecting keepsakes and posing for photographs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 1921, the Mexican president Álvaro Obregón along with the former revolutionary general visited Downtown Dallas's Mexican Park in Little Mexico; the small park was on the corner of Akard and Caruth Street, site of the current Fairmont Hotel.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The small neighborhood of Little Mexico was home to a Latin American population that had been drawn to Dallas by factors including the American Dream, better living conditions, and the Mexican Revolution.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Despite the onset of the Great Depression, business in construction was flourishing in 1930.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] That year, Columbus Marion "Dad" Joiner struck oil 100 miles (160 km) east of Dallas in Kilgore, spawning the East Texas oil boom.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas quickly became the financial center for the oil industry in Texas and Oklahoma.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] During World War II, Dallas was a major manufacturing center for military automobiles and aircraft for the United States and Allied forces.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Over 94,000 jeeps and over 6,000 military trucks were produced at the Ford plant in East Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] North American Aviation manufactured over 18,000 aircraft at their plant in Dallas, including the T-6 Texan trainer, P-51 Mustang fighter, and B-24 Liberator bomber.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] On November 22, 1963, United States President John F.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Kennedy was assassinated on Elm Street while his motorcade passed through Dealey Plaza in Downtown Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The upper two floors of the building from which the Warren Commission reported assassin Lee Harvey Oswald shot Kennedy have been converted into a historical museum covering the former president's life and accomplishments.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Kennedy was pronounced dead at Dallas Parkland Memorial Hospital just over 30 minutes after the shooting.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] On July 7, 2016, multiple shots were fired at a Black Lives Matter protest in Downtown Dallas, held against the police killings of two black men from other states.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The gunman, later identified as Micah Xavier Johnson, began firing at police officers at 8:58 p.m., killing five officers and injuring nine.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] This marked the deadliest day for U.S. law enforcement since the September 11 attacks.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Johnson told police during a standoff that he was upset about recent police shootings of black men and wanted to kill whites, especially white officers.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] After hours of negotiation failed, police resorted to a robot-delivered bomb, killing Johnson inside Dallas College El Centro Campus.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The shooting occurred in an area of hotels, restaurants, businesses, and residential apartments only a few blocks away from Dealey Plaza.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas is situated in the Southern United States, in North Texas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] It is the county seat of Dallas County and portions of the city extend into neighboring Collin, Denton, Kaufman, and Rockwall counties.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Many suburbs surround Dallas; three enclaves are within the city boundaries—Cockrell Hill, Highland Park, and University Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 385.8 square miles (999.3 km2); 340.5 square miles (881.9 km2) of Dallas is land and 45.3 square miles (117.4 km2) of it (11.75%) is water.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas makes up one-fifth of the much larger urbanized area known as the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex, in which one quarter of all Texans live.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas's skyline has twenty buildings classified as skyscrapers, over 490 feet (150 m) in height.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Despite its tallest building not reaching 980 feet (300 m), Dallas does have a signature building in Bank of America Plaza which is lit up in neon but falls outside the top two hundred tallest buildings in the world.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Although some of Dallas's architecture dates from the late 19th and early 20th centuries, most of the notable architecture in the city is from the modernist and postmodernist eras.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Iconic examples of modernist architecture include Reunion Tower, the John Fitzgerald Kennedy Memorial, I.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Pei's Dallas City Hall and the Morton H.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Good examples of postmodernist skyscrapers are Fountain Place, Bank of America Plaza, Renaissance Tower, JPMorgan Chase Tower, and Comerica Bank Tower.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Downtown Dallas also has residential offerings in downtown, some of which are signature skyline buildings.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Several smaller structures are fashioned in the Gothic Revival style, such as the Kirby Building, and the neoclassical style, as seen in the Davis and Wilson Buildings.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] One architectural "hotbed" in the city is a stretch of historic houses along Swiss Avenue, which has all shades and variants of architecture from Victorian to neoclassical.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Dallas Downtown Historic District protects a cross-section of Dallas commercial architecture from the 1880s to the 1940s.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The city of Dallas is home to many areas, neighborhoods, and communities.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas can be divided into several geographical areas which include larger geographical sections of territory including many subdivisions or neighborhoods, forming macroneighborhoods.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Central Dallas is anchored by Downtown Dallas, the center of the city, along with Oak Lawn and Uptown, areas characterized by dense retail, restaurants, and nightlife.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Downtown Dallas has a variety of named districts, including the West End Historic District, the Arts District, the Main Street District, Farmers Market District, the City Center Business District, the Convention Center District, and the Reunion District.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] This area includes Uptown, Victory Park, Harwood, Oak Lawn, Dallas Design District, Trinity Groves, Turtle Creek, Cityplace, Knox/Henderson, Greenville, and West Village.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Its historic district has one of the largest collections of Frank Lloyd Wright-inspired prairie-style homes in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In the northeast quadrant of the city is Lake Highlands, one of Dallas's most unified middle-class neighborhoods.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Once a separate city founded in the mid-1800s, Oak Cliff was annexed in 1903 by Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] As one of the oldest areas in Dallas, the hilly North Oak Cliff is home to 5 of the 13 conservation districts in Dallas including the architecturally significant Kessler Park neighborhood and trendy Bishop Arts District.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] South Dallas is the location of Cedars, and Fair Park, where the annual State Fair of Texas is held from late September through mid-October.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Also located here is Exposition Park, Dallas, noted for having artists, art galleries, and bars along tree-lined Exposition Avenue.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] South Side Dallas is a popular location for nightly entertainment.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The neighborhood has undergone extensive development and community integration.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] What was once an area characterized by high rates of poverty and crime is now one of the city's most attractive social and living destinations.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Further east, in the southeast quadrant of the city, is the large neighborhood of Pleasant Grove.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Once an independent city, it is a collection of mostly lower-income residential areas stretching to Seagoville in the southeast.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Though a city neighborhood, Pleasant Grove is surrounded by undeveloped land on all sides.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Swampland and wetlands separating it from South Dallas are part of the Great Trinity Forest, a subsection of the city's Trinity River Project, newly appreciated for habitat and flood control.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas and its surrounding area are mostly flat.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The city lies at elevations ranging from 450 to 550 feet (137 to 168 m) above sea level.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The western edge of the Austin Chalk Formation, a limestone escarpment (also known as the "White Rock Escarpment"), rises 230 feet (70 m) and runs roughly north–south through Dallas County.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] South of the Trinity River, the uplift is particularly noticeable in the neighborhoods of Oak Cliff and the adjacent cities of Cockrell Hill, Cedar Hill, Grand Prairie, and Irving.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Marked variations in terrain are also found in cities immediately to the west in Tarrant County surrounding Fort Worth, as well as along Turtle Creek north of Downtown.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas, like many other cities, was founded along a river.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The city was founded at the location of a "white rock crossing" of the Trinity River, where it was easier for wagons to cross the river in the days before ferries or bridges.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Trinity River, though not usefully navigable, is the major waterway through the city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] I-35E parallels its path through Dallas along the Stemmons Corridor, then south alongside the western portion of Downtown and past South Dallas and Pleasant Grove, where the river is paralleled by Interstate 45 until it exits the city and heads southeast towards Houston.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The river is flanked on both sides by 50 feet (15 m) tall earthen levees to protect the city from frequent floods.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The project area reaches for over 20 miles (32 km) in length within the city, while the overall geographical land area addressed by the Land Use Plan is approximately 44,000 acres (180 km2) in size—about 20% of the land area in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Green space along the river encompasses approximately 10,000 acres (40 km2), making it one of the largest and diverse urban parks in the world.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] White Rock Lake and Joe Pool Lake are reservoirs that comprise Dallas's other significant water features.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Built at the beginning of the 20th century, White Rock Lake Park is a popular destination for boaters, rowers, joggers, and bikers, as well as visitors seeking peaceful respite from the city at the 66-acre (267,000 m2) Dallas Arboretum and Botanical Garden, on the lake's eastern shore.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] White Rock Creek feeds into White Rock Lake and then exits into the Trinity River southeast of Downtown Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Trails along White Rock Creek are part of the extensive Dallas County Trails System.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Bachman Lake, just northwest of Love Field Airport, is a smaller lake also popularly used for recreation.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Northeast of the city is Lake Ray Hubbard, a vast 22,745-acre (92 km2) reservoir in an extension of Dallas surrounded by the suburbs of Garland, Rowlett, Rockwall, and Sunnyvale.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] To the west of the city is Mountain Creek Lake, once home to the Naval Air Station Dallas (Hensley Field) and a number of defense aircraft manufacturers.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen climate classification: *Cfa*, Trewartha: *Cfhk*) characteristic of the Southern Plains of the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] It also has both continental and tropical characteristics, characterized by a relatively wide annual temperature range for the latitude.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Located at the lower end of Tornado Alley, it is prone to extreme weather, tornadoes, and hailstorms.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Summers in Dallas are very hot with high humidity, although extended periods of dry weather often occur.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] July and August are typically the hottest months, with an average high of 96.0 °F (36 °C) and an average low of 76.7 °F (25 °C).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Heat indices regularly surpass 105 °F (41 °C) due to elevated humidity during the summer months, making the summer heat almost unbearable.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The all-time record high is 113 °F (45 °C), set on June 26 and 27, 1980 during the Heat Wave of 1980 at nearby Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Winters in Dallas are usually mild, with occasional cold spells.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The average date of first frost is November 12, and the average date of last frost is March 12.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] January is typically the coldest month, with an average daytime high of 56.8 °F (14 °C) and an average nighttime low of 37.3 °F (3 °C).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Snow accumulation is seen in the city in about 70% of winter seasons, and snowfall generally occurs 1–2 days out of the year for a seasonal average of 1.5 inches (4 cm).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Some areas in the region, however, receive more than that, while other areas receive negligible snowfall or none at all.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The all-time record low temperature within the city is −10 °F (−23 °C), set on February 12, 1899, during the Great Blizzard of 1899.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The temperature at nearby Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport reached −2 °F (−19 °C) on February 16, 2021, during the February 2021 North American winter storm.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Spring and autumn are transitional seasons with moderate and pleasant weather.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Vibrant wildflowers (such as the bluebonnet, Indian paintbrush and other flora) bloom in spring and are planted around the highways throughout Texas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Springtime weather can be quite volatile, but temperatures themselves are mild.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Late spring to early summer also tends to be the most humid, with humidity levels frequently exceeding 75%.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The weather in Dallas is also generally pleasant from late September to early December and on many winter days.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Autumn often brings more storms and tornado threats, but they are usually fewer and less severe than in spring.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Each spring, cold fronts moving south from the North collide with warm, humid air streaming in from the Gulf Coast, leading to severe thunderstorms with lightning, torrents of rain, hail, and occasionally, tornadoes.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Over time, tornadoes have probably been the most significant natural threat to the city, as it is near the heart of Tornado Alley.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] A few times each winter in Dallas, warm and humid air from the south will override cold, dry air, resulting in freezing rain or ice and causing disruptions in the city if the roads and highways become slick.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Temperatures reaching 70 °F (21 °C) on average occur on at least four days each winter month.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas averages 26 annual nights at or below freezing, with the winter of 1999–2000 holding the record for the fewest freezing nights with 14.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] During this same span of 15 years, the temperature in the region has only twice dropped below 15 °F (−9 °C), though it will generally fall below 20 °F (−7 °C) in most (67%) years.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Department of Agriculture places Dallas in Plant Hardiness Zone 8b.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] However, mild winter temperatures in the past 15 to 20 years had encouraged the horticulture of more cold-sensitive plants such as *Washingtonia filifera* and *Washingtonia filifera var. robusta* palms, nearly all of which died off during the February 2021 North American winter storm.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] According to the American Lung Association, Dallas has the 12th highest air pollution among U.S. cities, ranking it behind Los Angeles and Houston.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Much of the air pollution in Dallas and the surrounding area comes from a hazardous materials incineration plant in the small town of Midlothian and from cement plants in neighboring Ellis County.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The average daily low in Dallas is 57.4 °F (14 °C), and the average daily high is 76.9 °F (25 °C).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas receives approximately 39.1 inches (993 mm) of rain per year.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The record snowfall for Dallas was 11.2 inches (28 cm) on February 11, 2010.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas is the ninth-most-populous city in the United States and third in Texas after the cities of Houston and San Antonio.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Its metropolitan area encompasses one-quarter of the population of Texas, and is the largest in the Southern U.S. and Texas followed by the Greater Houston metropolitan area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] At the 2020 United States census the city of Dallas had 1,304,379 residents, an increase of 106,563 since the 2010 United States census.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Census Bureau estimates that Dallas, in the first years since the 2020 census, lost 4,835 people, leaving the city with a population of 1,299,544.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] There were 524,498 households at the 2020 estimates, up from 2010's 458,057 households, out of which 137,523 had children under the age of 18 living with them.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Approximately 36.2% of households were headed by married couples living together, 57.2% had a single householder male or female with no spouse present, and 35.6% were classified as non-family households with the householder living alone.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 2010, 33.7% of all households had one or more people under 18 years of age, and 17.6% had one or more people who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The average household size in 2020 was 2.52 and the average family size was 3.41.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 2018, the owner-occupied housing rate was 40.2% and the renter-occupied housing rate was 59.8%.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] At the 2010 census, the city's age distribution of the population showed 26.5% under the age of 18 and 8.8% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 2010, 50.0% of the population was male and 50.0% was female.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 2020, the median age 32.9 years; for every 100 females, there were 98.4 males.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] According to the 2020 American Community Survey, the median income for a household in the city was $54,747; families had a median household income of $60,895; married-couple families $81,761; and non-families $45,658.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 2003–2007's survey, male full-time workers had a median income of $32,265 versus $32,402 for female full-time workers.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The per capita income for the city was $25,904.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] About 18.7% of families and 21.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 33.6% of those under age 18 and 13.4% of those aged 65 or over.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Per 2007's survey, the median price for a house was $129,600; by 2020, the median price for a house was valued at $252,300, with 54.4% of owner-occupied units from $50,000 to $299,999.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The 2022 Point-In-Time Homeless Count found there were 4,410 homeless people in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The region surrounding Dallas is a habitat for mosquitoes, creating a pest problem for humans.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas and the surrounding area is sprayed regularly to control mosquito-borne diseases such as West Nile virus.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas's population was historically predominantly White (non-Hispanic Whites made up 82.8% of the population in 1930), but its population has diversified due to immigration and white flight over the 20th century.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Since then, the non-Hispanic White population has declined to less than one-third of the city's population.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Census Bureau's 2019 estimates, 29.1% were non-Hispanic White 24.3% Black and African American, 0.3% American Indian or Alaska Native, 3.7% Asian, and 1.4% from two or more races.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islanders made up a total of 312 residents according to 2019's census estimates, down from 606 in 2017.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Hispanic or Latino Americans of any race made up 41.2% of the estimated population in 2019.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Among the Hispanic or Latino American population in 2019, 34.6% of Dallas was Mexican, 0.4% Puerto Rican, 0.2% Cuban and 6.0% other Hispanic or Latino American.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 2017's American Community Survey estimates among the demographic 35.5% were Mexican, 0.6% Puerto Rican, 0.4% Cuban, and 5.4% other Hispanic or Latino.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] By 2020, Hispanic or Latino Americans of any race continued to constitute the largest ethnic group in the city proper, reflecting nationwide demographic trends.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Dallas area is a major living destination for Mexican Americans and other Hispanic and Latino American immigrants.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The southwestern portion of the city, particularly Oak Cliff is chiefly inhabited by Hispanic and Latino American residents.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The southeastern portion of the city Pleasant Grove is chiefly inhabited by African American and Hispanic or Latino American residents, while the southern portion of the city is predominantly black.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The west and east sides of the city are predominantly Hispanic or Latino American; Garland also has a large Spanish-speaking population.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] North Dallas has many enclaves of predominantly white, black and especially Hispanic or Latino American residents.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Dallas area is also a major living destination for Black and African Americans primarily due to its strong and diverse economy.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Between 2010 and 2020, the Dallas area had the second-most new Black and African American residents only behind the Atlanta area and slightly above the Houston area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The notable influx of African Americans is partly due to the New Great Migration.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] There is a significant number of people from the Horn of Africa, immigrants from Ethiopia, Eritrea and Somalia.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Dallas–Fort-Worth metroplex had an estimated 70,000 Russian-speakers (as of November 6, 2012) mostly immigrants from the former Soviet Bloc.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Included in this population are Russians, Russian Jews, Ukrainians, Armenians, Belarusians, Moldavians Uzbek, Kirghiz, and others.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Russian-speaking population of Dallas has continued to grow in the sector of "American husbands-Russian wives".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Russian DFW has its own newspaper, *The Dallas Telegraph*.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In addition, Dallas and its suburbs are home to a large number of Asian Americans including those of Indian, Vietnamese, Chinese, Korean, Filipino, Japanese, and other heritage.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Among large-sized cities in the United States, Plano, the northern suburb of Dallas, has the 6th largest Chinese American population as of 2016.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Plano-Richardson area in particular had an estimated 30,000 Iranian Americans in 2012.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] With so many immigrant groups, there are often multilingual signs in the linguistic landscape.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Census Bureau data released in December 2013, 23 percent of Dallas County residents were foreign-born, while 16 percent of Tarrant County residents were foreign-born.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The 2018 census estimates determined that the city of Dallas's foreign-born population consisted of 25.4% naturalized citizens and 74.6% non-citizens.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas and the Metroplex have one of the largest lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) populations in the country.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Throughout the year there are LGBT events held in the area, including the annual Alan Ross Texas Freedom (Pride) Parade and Festival in June, which draws approximately 50,000 attendees.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] For decades, the Oak Lawn and Bishop Arts districts have been known as the epicenters of LGBT culture in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Christianity is the most prevalently practiced religion in Dallas and the wider metropolitan area according to a 2014 study by the Pew Research Center (78%), and the Public Religion Research Institute's 2020 study (77%).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] There is a large Protestant Christian influence in the Dallas community, though the city of Dallas and Dallas County have more Catholic than Protestant residents, while the reverse is usually true for the suburban areas of Dallas and the city of Fort Worth.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas has been called the "Prison Ministry Capital of the World" by the prison ministry community.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] It is a home for the International Network of Prison Ministries, the Coalition of Prison Evangelists, Bill Glass Champions for Life, Chaplain Ray's International Prison Ministry, and 60 other prison ministries.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Methodist, Baptist, and Presbyterian churches are prominent in many neighborhoods and anchor two of the city's major private universities (Southern Methodist University and Dallas Baptist University).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas is also home to two evangelical seminaries: the Dallas Theological Seminary and Criswell College.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Many Bible schools including Christ For The Nations Institute are also headquartered in the city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Christian creationist apologetics group Institute for Creation Research is headquartered in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] According to the Pew Research Center, evangelical Protestantism constituted the largest form of Protestantism in the area as of 2014.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The largest single evangelical Protestant group were Baptists.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The largest Baptist denomination was the Southern Baptist Convention, followed by the historically black National Baptist Convention USA.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] African-initiated Protestant churches including Ethiopian Evangelical churches can be found throughout the metropolitan area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Catholic Church is also a significant religious organization in the Dallas area and operates the University of Dallas, a liberal-arts university in the Dallas suburb of Irving.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Cathedral Santuario de la Virgen de Guadalupe in the Arts District is home to the second-largest Catholic church membership in the United States and overseas, consisting over 70 parishes in the Dallas Diocese.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Society of Jesus operates the Jesuit College Preparatory School of Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas is also home to numerous Eastern Orthodox and Oriental Orthodox churches including Saint Seraphim Cathedral, see of the Orthodox Church in America's Southern Diocese.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of America (Ecumenical Patriarchate) has one parish in the city of Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Sarkis Armenian Church (serving as part of the Armenian Apostolic Church facility).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Jehovah's Witnesses has a large number of members throughout the Dallas metropolitan division.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In addition, there are several Unitarian Universalist congregations, including First Unitarian Church of Dallas, founded in 1899.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] A large community of the United Church of Christ exists in the city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The most prominent UCC-affiliated church is the Cathedral of Hope, a predominantly LGBT-affirming church.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has a sizeable community in the Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Members in the area are organized into 24 stakes.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The Dallas Texas Temple, dedicated in 1984 as the first temple in Texas, is located in the city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Two more temples, the Fort Worth Texas Temple and Fairview Texas Temple, are under construction in the area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Since the establishment of the city's first Jewish cemetery in 1854 and its first congregation (which would eventually be known as Temple Emanu-El) in 1873, Dallasite Jews have been well represented among leaders in commerce, politics, and various professional fields in Dallas and elsewhere.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Furthermore, a large Muslim community exists in the north and northeastern portions of Dallas, as well as in the northern Dallas suburbs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] The oldest mosque in Dallas is Masjid Al-Islam just south of Downtown.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Immigrants from East Asia, Southeast Asia, Nepal, and Sri Lanka have all contributed to the Buddhist population, which is concentrated in the northern suburbs of Garland, Plano and Richardson.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Numerous Buddhist temples dot the Metroplex including The Buddhist Center of Dallas, Lien Hoa Vietnamese Temple of Irving, and Kadampa Meditation Center Texas and Wat Buddhamahamunee of Arlington.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] A large and growing Hindu Community lives in the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Most live in Collin County and the northern portions of Dallas County.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Over 28 Hindu Temples exist in the area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Some notable ones include the DFW Hindu Temple, the North Texas Hindu Mandir, Radha Krishna Temple, Dallas and Karya Siddhi Hanuman Temple.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] There are also at least three Sikh Gurudwaras in this metropolitan area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] For irreligious people, the Winter Solstice Celebration is held in the Metroplex although some of its participants are also neo-pagans and New Agers.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] According to the FBI, a city to city comparison of crime rates can be misleading, because recording practices vary from city to city, citizens report different percentages of crimes from one city to the next, and the actual number of people physically present in a city is unknown.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] With that in mind, Dallas has one of the top 10 crime rates in Texas and its crime rate is higher than the national average.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Since 2020, Dallas's murder rate has seen a notable increase.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] In 2020, Dallas recorded 251 murders which was a 20-year high.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] By 2022 it decreased to 214 but then increased to 246 in 2023.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] As of 2020, the gang presence in Dallas has grown significantly and is heavily responsible for the spike in crime.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p01] Dallas leaders have made crime reduction a major priority.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In its beginnings, Dallas relied on farming, neighboring Fort Worth's Stockyards, and its prime location on Native American trade routes to sustain itself.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas's key to growth came in 1873 with the construction of multiple rail lines through the city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] As Dallas grew and technology developed, cotton became its boon and by 1900, Dallas was the largest inland cotton market in the world, becoming a leader in cotton gin machinery manufacturing.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] By the early 1900s, Dallas was a hub for economic activity all over the Southern United States and was selected in 1914 as the seat of the Eleventh Federal Reserve District.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] By 1925, Texas churned out more than 1⁄3 of the nation's cotton crop, with 31% of Texas cotton produced within a 100-mile (160 km) radius of Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In the 1930s, petroleum was discovered east of Dallas, near Kilgore.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas's proximity to the discovery put it immediately at the center of the nation's petroleum market.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Petroleum discoveries in the Permian Basin, the Panhandle, the Gulf Coast, and Oklahoma in the following years further solidified Dallas's position as the hub of the market.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The end of World War II left Dallas seeded with a nexus of communications, engineering, and production talent by companies such as Collins Radio Corporation.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Decades later, the telecommunications and information revolutions still drive a large portion of the local economy.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The city is sometimes referred to as the heart of "Silicon Prairie" because of a high concentration of telecommunications companies in the region, the epicenter of which lies along the Telecom Corridor in Richardson, a northern suburb of Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Texas Instruments, a major manufacturer, employs 10,400 people at its corporate headquarters and chip plants in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In the 1980s Dallas was a real estate hotbed, with the increasing metropolitan population bringing with it a demand for new housing and office space.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Several of Downtown Dallas's largest buildings are the fruit of this boom, but over-speculation, the savings and loan crisis and an oil bust brought the 1980s building boom to an end for Dallas as well as its sister city Houston.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Between the late 1980s and the early 2000s, central Dallas went through a slow period of growth.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] However, since the early 2000s the central core of Dallas has been enjoying steady and significant growth encompassing both repurposing of older commercial buildings in Downtown Dallas into residential and hotel uses, as well as the construction of new office and residential towers.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The opening of Klyde Warren Park, built across Woodall Rodgers Freeway seamlessly connecting the central Dallas CBD to Uptown/Victory Park, has acted synergistically with the highly successful Dallas Arts District, so both have become catalysts for significant new development in central Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The residential real estate market in the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex has not only been resilient but has once again returned to a boom status.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas and the greater metro area have been leading the nation in apartment construction and net leasing, with rents reaching all-time highs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Single family home sales, whether pre-owned or new construction, along with home price appreciation, were leading the nation since 2015.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] A sudden drop in the price of oil, starting in mid-2014 and accelerating throughout 2015, has not significantly affected Dallas and its greater metro area due to the highly diversified nature of its economy.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas and the metropolitan region continue to see strong demand for housing, apartment and office leasing, shopping center space, warehouse and industrial space with overall job growth remaining very robust.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Oil-dependent cities and regions have felt significant effects from the downturn, but Dallas's growth has continued unabated, strengthening in 2015.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Dallas–Fort Worth area has one of the largest concentrations of corporate headquarters for publicly traded companies in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] *Fortune Magazine*'s 2022 annual list of the Fortune 500 in America indicates the city of Dallas had 11 Fortune 500 companies and the DFW region as a whole had 23.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] As of 2022, Dallas–Fort Worth represents the second-largest concentration of Fortune 500 headquarters in Texas and fourth-largest in the United States, behind the metropolitan areas of Houston (24), Chicago (35) and New York (62).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In 2008, AT&T relocated their headquarters to Downtown Dallas; AT&T is the largest telecommunications company in the world and was the ninth largest company in the nation by revenue for 2017.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In October 2016, Jacobs Engineering, one of the world's largest engineering companies, relocated from Pasadena, California to Downtown Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Nearby Irving is home to six Fortune 500 companies of its own, including McKesson, the country's largest pharmaceutical distributor and listed at number seven overall on the 2021 Fortune 500 list, Fluor (engineering), Kimberly-Clark, Celanese, Michaels Companies, and Vistra Energy.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Plano is home to an additional four Fortune 500 companies, including J.C.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Penney, Alliance Data Systems, Yum China, and Dr.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Fort Worth is home to two Fortune 500 companies, including American Airlines, the largest airline in the world by revenue, fleet size, profit, passengers carried and revenue passenger mile and D.R.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Horton, the largest homebuilder in America.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Westlake, TX, north of Fort Worth, now has two Fortune 500 companies: Financial services giant, Charles Schwab, and convenience store distributor, Core-Mark.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] One Fortune 500 company, GameStop, is based in Grapevine.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Cheese's, Zale Corporation, and Fossil, Inc.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Many of these companies—and others throughout the DFW metroplex—comprise the Dallas Regional Chamber.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Komen for the Cure, the world's largest breast cancer organization, was founded and is headquartered in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In addition to its large number of businesses, Dallas has more shopping centers per capita than any other city in the United States and is also home to the second shopping center ever built in the United States, Highland Park Village, which opened in 1931.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas is home of the two other major malls in North Texas, the Dallas Galleria and NorthPark Center, which is the second largest mall in Texas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Both malls feature high-end stores and are major tourist draws for the region.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Tourism is an important sector of Dallas's economy and is its tenth largest employer, providing 56,000 jobs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas receives on average 25 million visitors annually.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Arts District in the northern section of Downtown is home to several arts venues and is the largest contiguous arts district in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Notable venues in the district include the Dallas Museum of Art; the Morton H.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Meyerson Symphony Center, home to the Dallas Symphony Orchestra and Dallas Wind Symphony; the Nasher Sculpture Center; and the Trammell & Margaret Crow Collection of Asian Art.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Perot Museum of Nature and Science, also in Downtown Dallas, is a natural history and science museum.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Designed by 2005 Pritzker Architecture Prize Laureate Thom Mayne and his firm Morphosis Architects, the 180,000-square-foot (17,000 m2) facility has six floors and stands about 14 stories high.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Not far north of the area is the Meadows Museum at Southern Methodist University.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In 2009, it joined up with Madrid's Prado Museum for a three-year partnership.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Prado focuses on Spanish visual art and has a collection of Spanish art in North America, with works by de Juanes, El Greco, Fortuny, Goya, Murillo, Picasso, Pkensa, Ribera, Rico, Velasquez, Zurbaran, and other Spaniards.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] These works, as well as non-Spanish highlights like sculptures by Rodin and Moore, have been so successful of a collaboration that the Prado and Meadows have agreed upon an extension of the partnership.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The former Texas School Book Depository, from which, according to the Warren Commission Report, Lee Harvey Oswald shot and killed President John F.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Kennedy in 1963, has served since the 1980s as a county government office building, except for its sixth and seventh floors, which house the Sixth Floor Museum.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The American Museum of the Miniature Arts is at the Hall of State in Fair Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Arts District is also home to DISD's Booker T.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Washington High School for the Performing and Visual Arts, a magnet school that was recently expanded.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] City Center District, next to the Arts District, is home to the Dallas Contemporary.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Institute for Creation Research operates the ICR Discovery Center for Science & Earth History, a creationism museum, in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Deep Ellum, immediately east of Downtown, originally became popular during the 1920s and 1930s as the prime jazz and blues hot spot in the South.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Artists such as Blind Lemon Jefferson, Robert Johnson, Huddie "Lead Belly" Ledbetter, and Bessie Smith played in original Deep Ellum clubs such as the Harlem and the Palace.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Today, Deep Ellum is home to hundreds of artists who live in lofts or operate in studios throughout the district alongside bars, pubs, and concert venues.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] A major art infusion in the area results from the city's lax stance on graffiti, and a number of public spaces, including tunnels, sides of buildings, sidewalks, and streets, are covered in murals.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] One major example, the Good-Latimer tunnel, was torn down in late 2006 to accommodate the construction of a light rail line through the site.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Like Deep Ellum before it, the Cedars neighborhood to the south of Downtown has also seen a growing population of studio artists and an expanding roster of entertainment venues.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The area's art scene began to grow in the early 2000s with the opening of Southside on Lamar, an old Sears Roebuck and Company warehouse converted into lofts, studios, and retail.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Current attractions include Gilley's Dallas and Poor David's Pub.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas Mavericks owner and local entrepreneur Mark Cuban purchased land along Lamar Street near Cedars Station in September 2005, and locals speculate he is planning an entertainment complex for the site.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] South of the Trinity River, the Bishop Arts District in Oak Cliff is home to a number of studio artists living in converted warehouses.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Walls of buildings along alleyways and streets are painted with murals, and the surrounding streets contain many eclectic restaurants and shops.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas has an Office of Cultural Affairs as a department of the city government.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The office is responsible for six cultural centers throughout the city, funding for local artists and theaters, initiating public art projects, and running the city-owned classical radio station WRR.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Los Angeles-class submarine USS *Dallas* was planned to become a museum ship near the Trinity River after her decommissioning in September 2014, but this has since been delayed.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] It will be taken apart into massive sections in Houston and be transported by trucks to the museum site and will be put back together.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The city is served by the Dallas Public Library system.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The system was created by the Dallas Federation of Women's Clubs with efforts spearheaded by then president May Dickson Exall.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Her fundraising efforts led to a grant from philanthropist and steel baron Andrew Carnegie, which allowed the library system to build its first branch in 1901.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Today, the library operates 30 branch locations throughout the city, including the 8-story J.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Erik Jonsson Central Library in the Government District of Downtown.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas is known for its barbecue, authentic Mexican, and Tex-Mex cuisine.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Famous products of the Dallas culinary scene include the Frozen margarita machine by restaurateur Mariano Martinez in 1971.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The State Fair of Texas has been held annually at Fair Park since 1886, and generates an estimated $50 million to the city's economy annually.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Red River Shootout, a football game that pits the University of Texas at Austin against the University of Oklahoma at the Cotton Bowl, also brings significant crowds to the city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The city also hosts the State Fair Classic and Heart of Dallas Bowl at the Cotton Bowl.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] With the opening of Victory Park, WFAA began hosting an annual New Year's Eve celebration in AT&T Plaza that the television station hoped would be reminiscent of celebrations in New York's Times Square; New Year's Eve 2011 set a new record of 32,000 people in attendance.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] After the discontinuance of the "Big D NYE" festivities a few years later, a new end-of-year event was started downtown, with a big fireworks show put on at Reunion Tower, which has since aired on KXAS and other TV stations around the state and region.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Also, several Omni hotels in the Dallas area host large events to welcome in the new year, including murder mystery parties, rave-inspired events, and other events.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Downtown Dallas is home to two major league sports teams that play at the American Airlines Center: the Dallas Mavericks (NBA), who won the NBA Championship in 2011, and the Dallas Stars (NHL), who won the Stanley Cup in 1999.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Nearby Arlington is home to the Dallas Cowboys (NFL), who play at the AT&T Stadium and have won five Super Bowls, the Texas Rangers (MLB), who play at Globe Life Field and won the World Series in 2023, and the Dallas Wings (WNBA), who play at College Park Center.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] MLS team FC Dallas plays at Toyota Stadium in Frisco and won the Lamar Hunt U.S.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The newest team in Dallas is Dallas Trinity FC, the first professional women's soccer team that plays at the historic Cotton Bowl (stadium).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The city is home to several minor league and college sports programs in the area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Since joining the league as an expansion team in 1960, the Cowboys have enjoyed substantial success, advancing to eight Super Bowls and winning five.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Cowboys are financially the most valuable sports franchise in the world, worth approximately $4 billion.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In 2009, they relocated to their new 80,000-seat stadium in Arlington, which was the site of Super Bowl XLV and is set to host the most matches during the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Cowboys are currently part of the East Division of the National Football Conference (NFC).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Texas Rangers won the American League pennant in 2010, 2011 and 2023, and won the World Series in 2023.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The franchise relocated from Washington D.C. in 1972.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] They play in the West Division of the American League.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Dallas Mavericks joined the league as an expansion team in 1980.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] They won their first National Basketball Association championship in 2011 led by Dirk Nowitzki.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] They play in the Southwest Division of the Western Conference.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Dallas Stars moved to North Texas in 1993 as a relocation from the former team, the Minnesota North Stars.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Stars have won eight division titles in Dallas, two Presidents' Trophies as the top regular season team in the NHL, the Western Conference championship three times, and in 1998–99, the Stanley Cup.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The team plays in the Central Division of the Western Conference.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] FC Dallas play at Toyota Stadium (formerly FC Dallas Stadium and Pizza Hut Park), a stadium that opened in 2005.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] They currently play in MLS's Western Conference.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The team was originally called the Dallas Burn and used to play in the Cotton Bowl.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Although FC Dallas has not yet won a MLS Cup, they won the Lamar Hunt U.S.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Open Cup in 1997 and 2016 and the Supporters' Shield in 2016.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Previously, the Dallas Tornado played in the North American Soccer League from 1968 to 1981.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Dallas Wings came to The Metroplex in 2016 after relocating from Tulsa.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] There are many notable minor league teams in the Dallas-Fort Worth.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Allen Americans are a professional ice hockey team headquartered at the Credit Union of Texas Event Center in Allen, Texas, which currently plays in the ECHL.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] They are the minor league affiliate of the NHL's Seattle Kraken.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The team was founded in 2009 in the Central Hockey League(CHL).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Dallas Renegades are a professional football team in the UFL that plays their home games at Toyota Stadium.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Dallas Sidekicks (2012) are an American professional indoor soccer team based in Allen, Texas, a suburb of Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] They play their home games in the Credit Union of Texas Event Center.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The team is named after the original Dallas Sidekicks that operated from 1984 to 2004.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The MLS-affiliated North Texas SC team is a member of MLS Next Pro and plays in Frisco at Toyota Stadium; it is the reserve team of FC Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Dallas Mavericks own an NBA G League team, the Texas Legends.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Rugby is a developing sport in Dallas and Texas in general.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The multiple clubs, ranging from men's and women's clubs to collegiate and high school, are part of the Texas Rugby Football Union.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas was one of only 16 cities in the United States included in the Rugby Super League, represented by Dallas Harlequins.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Australian rules football is also growing in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Dallas Magpies, founded in 1998, compete in the United States Australian Football League.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The only Division I sports program within the Dallas political boundary is the Dallas Baptist University Patriots baseball team.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Although outside the city limits, the Mustangs of Southern Methodist University are in the enclave of University Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Neighboring cities Fort Worth, Arlington, and Denton are home to the Texas Christian University Horned Frogs, UT Arlington Mavericks, and University of North Texas Mean Green respectively.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Dallas area hosted the Final Four of the 2014 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament at AT&T Stadium.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The college Cotton Bowl Classic football game was played at the Cotton Bowl through its 2009 game, but has moved to AT&T Stadium.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Red River Showdown is an American college football rivalry game played annually at the Cotton Bowl Stadium during the second weekend of the State Fair of Texas in October.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The game is played by the Oklahoma Sooners football team of the University of Oklahoma and the Texas Longhorns football team of the University of Texas at Austin.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The 10,000-capacity Forester Stadium, which is used mainly for football and soccer, is also located in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas Trinity FC is the first professional women's soccer team in Dallas that plays at the historic Cotton Bowl (stadium) located in Downtown Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Originally founded in May 2023 by the Neil family and managed by Chris Petrucelli, the club kicked off its inaugural season in August 2024 when they played Tampa Bay Sun FC, ending in a 1 v 1 tie.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Following this match was two very significant matches for the club, the friendly match and home opener.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The club played their friendly match vs FC Barcelona Femení where they lost 0-6 and the club's official home match was against DC Power FC where they tied 1-1.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The club finished the season 12–9–7, finishing third and getting eliminated by Tampa Bay Sun FC by the final score of 2–1 in the semi-finals of the USL Championship.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Following its inaugural season, the teams parted ways with Pauline MacDonald and Gavin Beith.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Recently, the team announced its State Fair Clasico Match during the Texas State Fair at Fair Park on October 18 vs Club América Femenil.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Major League Volleyball expanded to the Dallas market after announcing plans for a single, unified professional women's volleyball league with the former Pro Volleyball Federation (PVF) in 2025.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Dallas franchise of Major League Volleyball was officially named Dallas Pulse and confirmed Comerica Center in Frisco as its home court for their 2026 debut.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In their inaugural season, the Pulse have clinched a postseason spot with Head Coach, Shannon Winzer, as they prepare to host the 2026 MLV Championship at Comerica Center.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas maintains and operates 406 parks on 21,000 acres (85 km2) of parkland.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The city's parks contain 17 separate lakes, including White Rock and Bachman lakes, spanning a total of 4,400 acres (17.81 km2).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Built in 1936 for the Texas Centennial Exposition world's fair, Fair Park is the world's largest collection of Art Deco exhibit buildings, art, and sculptures; Fair Park is also home to the State Fair of Texas, the largest state fair in the United States with 2 million visitors.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In November 2019, consultants presented to the public a master plan to revitalize the area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Named after Klyde Warren, the young son of billionaire Kelcy Warren, the 5.2-acre Klyde Warren Park was built above Woodall Rodgers Freeway and connects Uptown and Downtown, specifically the Arts District.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Klyde Warren Park is home to an amphitheater, jogging trails, a children's park, a dog park, a putting green, croquet, ping pong, chess, an outdoor library, and two restaurants.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Food trucks give another option of dining and are lined along the park's Downtown side.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] There are also weekly planned events, including yoga, Zumba, skyline tours, tai chi, and meditation.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Klyde Warren Park is home to a free trolley stop on Olive St., which riders can connect to Downtown, McKinney Avenue, and West Village.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Built in 1913, Turtle Creek Parkway park is a 23.7-acre (9.6 ha) linear park in between Turtle Creek and Turtle Creek Boulevard in the aptly named Turtle Creek neighborhood.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Archaeological surveys discovered dart points and flint chips dating 3,000 years to 1,000 BCE.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] This site was later discovered to be home to Native Americans who cherished the trees and natural spring water.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The park is across Turtle Creek from Kalita Humphreys Theater, designed by Frank Lloyd Wright.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Opened on July 4, 1906, Lake Cliff Park was called "the Southwest's Greatest Playground".
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The park was home to an amusement park, a large pool, waterslides, the world's largest skating rink, and three theaters, the largest being the 2,500-seat Casino Theater.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] After the streetcar bridge that brought most of the park visitors collapsed, Lake Cliff Park was sold.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Casino Theater moved and the pool was demolished after a polio scare in 1959.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The pool was Dallas's first municipal pool.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In 1935, Dallas purchased 36 acres (15 ha) from John Cole's estate to develop Reverchon Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Reverchon Park was named after botanist Julien Reverchon, who left France to live in the La Reunion colony, which was founded in the mid-1800s and was situated in present-day West Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Reverchon Park was planned to be the crown jewel of the Dallas park system and was even referred to as the "Central Park" of Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Improvements were made throughout the years, including the Iris Bowl, picnic settings, a baseball diamond, and tennis courts.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Iris Bowl celebrated many Greek pageants, dances, and other performances.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Gill Well was installed for nearby residents and drew people all across Texas who wanted to experience the water's healing powers.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The baseball diamond was host to a 1953 exhibition game for the New York Giants and the Cleveland Indians.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] As part of the ongoing Trinity River Project, the Great Trinity Forest, at 6,000 acres (24 km2), is the largest urban hardwood forest in the United States and is part of the largest urban park in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Trinity River Audubon Center is a new addition to the park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Opened in 2008, it serves as a gateway to many trails and other nature-viewing activities in the area.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Trinity River Audubon Center is the first LEED-certified building built by the City of Dallas Parks and Recreation Department.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Named after its former railroad name, the Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad (or "MKT" Railroad), the 3.5-mile (5.6 km) stretch of railroad was purchased by the city of Dallas and transformed into the city's premier trail.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Stretching from Victory Park, the 30-acre (12 ha) Katy Trail passes through the Turtle Creek and Knox Park neighborhoods and runs along the east side of Highland Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The trail ends at Central Expressway, but extensions are underway to extend the trail to the White Rock Lake Trail in Lakewood.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas hosts three of the twenty-one preserves of the extensive 3,200 acres (13 km2) Dallas County Preserve System.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Joppa Preserve, the McCommas Bluff Preserve, and the Cedar Ridge Preserve are within the Dallas city limits.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Cedar Ridge Preserve was known as the Dallas Nature Center, but the Audubon Dallas group now manages the 633-acre (2.56 km2) natural habitat park on behalf of the city of Dallas and Dallas County.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The preserve sits at an elevation of 755 feet (230 m) above sea level and offers a variety of outdoor activities, including 10 miles (16 km) of hiking trails and picnic areas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The city is also home to Texas's first and largest zoo, the 106-acre (0.43 km2) Dallas Zoo, which opened at its current location in 1888.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The city uses a council-manager government, with Eric Johnson serving as mayor, Kimberly Tolbert serving as city manager, and 14 council members serving as representatives to the 14 council districts in the city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] This organizational structure was contested by some in favor of a strong-mayor city charter, only to be rejected by Dallas voters.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Martínez become the first Latin American to sit as a councilwoman in Dallas's city council.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In the 2017–2018 fiscal year, the city's total budget (the sum of operating and capital budgets) was $3.3 billion.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The United States District Court for the Northern District of Texas, which exercises original jurisdiction over 100 counties in North and West Texas, convenes in the Earle Cabell Federal Building and Courthouse in the Government District of Downtown.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The same building additionally houses United States Bankruptcy and Magistrate Courts and a United States Attorney office.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas also is the seat of the Fifth Court of Appeals of Texas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Since 2023, Dallas has been the largest city in the United States with a Republican mayor after Eric Johnson switched parties after winning re-election.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Democratic voters dominate the majority of the city, especially the central urban core and southern sectors, with Republicans spreading a sliver of suburban neighborhoods in North Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In the 2004 U.S. presidential election, 57% of voters in Dallas's city limits voted for John Kerry over George W.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas County was closely divided, with 50% of voters voting for Bush and 49% voting for Kerry.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Results in the 2008 and 2012 elections favored Barack Obama, with the 44th President receiving 57% of Dallas County voters in both years, with greater margins in the city of Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In the 2016 U.S. presidential election, approximately 66% of Dallas voters voted for Hillary Clinton, with 28% of city voters voting for Donald Trump.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas County as a whole saw 61% of voters voting for Clinton, with 35% support for Trump.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In 2004, Lupe Valdez was elected Dallas County Sheriff.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] An open lesbian, Valdez was the only female sheriff in the state of Texas until her resignation.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Despite controversies in her handling of county jails, she won re-election in 2008 with a 10-point victory over Republican challenger Lowell Cannaday.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In the 2024 United States presidential election, Donald Trump, achieved 34.1% of the vote in the city of Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] This marked the highest level of support for a Republican candidate in the city since the 2012 election, when Mitt Romney received a comparable percentage.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Trump's performance in Dallas has been attributed in part to a notable shift in Hispanic voter preferences within Texas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Trump garnered an estimated 55% of the Hispanic vote statewide, a significant improvement from his performance among Hispanic voters in 2016.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] There are 337 public schools, 89 private schools, 38 colleges, and 32 libraries in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Dallas–Fort Worth is also home to six Nobel Laureates.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Dallas area has a high number of colleges and universities.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In addition to those in the city, the surrounding cities also have a number of universities, colleges, trade schools, and other educational institutions.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Texas Legislature defines all areas in Dallas County and in the Carrollton-Farmers Branch Independent School District as being in the service area of Dallas College (formerly Dallas County Community College District or DCCCD).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Areas in Collin County are assigned to Collin College.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Most areas in the city of Dallas are within the Dallas Independent School District, the 12th-largest school district in the United States and second largest in Texas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The school district operates independently of the city and enrolls over 161,000 students.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] As of 2003 DISD has the majority of K–12 students in the city of Dallas, and a proportionately larger number of students who are not non-Hispanic white.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] A few areas of Dallas also extend into other school districts in Dallas County, including Carrollton-Farmers Branch, Coppell, Duncanville, Garland, Highland Park, Irving, Mesquite, and Richardson.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Portions of Dallas in Collin County are in Plano ISD, and portions of Dallas in Denton County are in the Carrollton-Farmers Branch ISD.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The Wilmer-Hutchins Independent School District once served portions of southern Dallas, but it was shut down for the 2005–2006 year.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] WHISD students started attending other Dallas ISD schools during that time.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Following the close, the Texas Education Agency consolidated WHISD into Dallas ISD.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] In 2003 Royce Hanson, author of *Civic Culture and Urban Change: Governing Dallas*, stated that the Plano, Richardson, and Wilmer-Hutchins school districts were the "most significant" of the public school students with students in Dallas who were not in Dallas ISD.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Many school districts in Dallas County, including Dallas ISD, were formerly served by a governmental agency called Dallas County Schools.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] The system provided busing and other transportation services, access to a massive media library, technology services, strong ties to local organizations for education/community integration, and staff development programs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p02] Students from Dallas attend many private schools in Dallas, and in nearby areas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Dallas has several local newspapers, magazines, television stations and radio stations that serve the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex, which is the fifth-largest media market in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Dallas has one major daily newspaper, *The Dallas Morning News*, which was founded in 1885 by A.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The *Dallas Times Herald*, started in 1888, was the *Morning News'* major competitor until Belo purchased it on December 8, 1991, and closed the paper down the next day.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Other daily newspapers are *Al Día*, a Spanish-language paper published by Belo, and a number of ethnic newspapers printed in languages such as Chinese, Korean, and Vietnamese.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Other publications include the *Dallas Weekly* and the *Elite News*, all weekly news publications.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The *Dallas Observer* and the *North Texas Journal* are also alternative weekly newspapers.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] *The Dallas Morning News* formerly had a weekly publication, *Neighborsgo*, which came out every Friday and focused on community news.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Readers could post stories and contribute content to the website.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] In terms of the larger metro area, the *Fort Worth Star-Telegram* is another major daily newspaper, covering Fort Worth's metropolitan division.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] It also publishes a major Spanish-language newspaper for the entire metro area known as *La Estrella*.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] To the north of Dallas and Fort Worth, the *Denton Record-Chronicle* primarily covers news for the city of Denton and Denton County.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] KTXA 21 and KFAA 29 are an independent stations; KTXA was previously affiliated with the now-defunct UPN network.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Over 101 radio stations operate within range of Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The city of Dallas operates WRR 101.1 FM, the area's main classical music station, from city offices in Fair Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Its original sister station, licensed as WRR in 1921, is the oldest commercially operated radio station in Texas and claims to be the second-oldest in the United States, after KDKA in Pittsburgh.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] KKDA-FM (K104), an urban contemporary station, and KRNB (Smooth R&B 105.7), an urban adult contemporary station, are owned independently by Service Broadcasting Corporation.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Slavic Voice of America media group serves Russian-speaking Americans out of Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Hispanic Broadcasting Corporation (HBC), the largest company in the Spanish-language radio station business, is based in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] In 2003, HBC was acquired by Univision and became Univision Radio Inc., but the radio company remains headquartered in the city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The Dallas Police Department provides most policing in Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The Dallas Chief of Police is Daniel Comeaux.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The police headquarters are in the Cedars neighborhood of southern Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Emergency medical services and fire protection in the city are provided by the Dallas Fire-Rescue Department.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The Dallas Fire & Rescue chief is Dominique Artis.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The department operates the Dallas Firefighter's Museum built in 1907 along Parry Avenue near Fair Park.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Dallas's oldest remaining fire station building still stands at the corner of McKinney Ave. and Leonard and was built in 1892.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Number 1, and is now a picture framing shop.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Dallas has many hospitals and several medical research facilities within its city limits.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] One major research center is the Dallas Medical District with the UT Southwestern Medical Center in the Stemmons Corridor, along with the affiliated UT Southwestern Medical School.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The health care complex includes within its bounds Parkland Memorial Hospital, Children's Medical Center, William P.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Paul University Hospital), and the William P.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Dallas also has a VA hospital in the southern portion of the city, the Dallas Veterans Affairs Medical Center.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The center is home to a Consolidated Mail Outpatient Pharmacy (CMOP), part of an initiative by the Department of Veterans Affairs to provide mail-order prescriptions to veterans using computerization at strategic locations throughout the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Dallas is served by Dallas Water Utilities, which operates several waste treatment plants and pulls water from several area reservoirs.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Several companies maintain the city's electric system, including Stream Energy, Cirro Energy and Oncor Electric Delivery, whose parent company, Energy Future Holdings Corporation, has headquarters in the city.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The city offers garbage pickup and recycling service weekly through its Sanitation Services department.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Telephone networks, broadband internet, and cable television service are available from several companies, including AT&T, Spectrum, and Verizon FiOS.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] In 2009, 78.5% of Dallas (city) commuters drive to work alone.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The 2009 mode share for Dallas (city) commuters are 10.7% for carpooling, 3.9% for transit, 1.9% for walking, and .1% for cycling.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] In 2015, the American Community Survey estimated modal shares for Dallas (city) commuters of 75.4% for driving alone, 12.8% for carpooling, 3.5% for riding transit, 1.9% for walking, and .2% for cycling.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The city of Dallas has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] In 2015, 10.2 percent of Dallas households lacked a car, decreased to 9.1 percent in 2016 and to 8.7 percent in 2023.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Dallas averaged 1.59 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Dallas is at the confluence of four major interstate highways—Interstates 20, 30, 35E, and 45.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The Dallas area freeway system is set up in the popular hub-and-spoke system, shaped much like a wagon wheel.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Starting from the center of the city, a small freeway loop surrounds Downtown, followed by the I-635 loop about 10 miles (16 km) outside Downtown, and ultimately the tolled President George Bush Turnpike.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Inside these freeway loops are other boulevard- and parkway-style loops, including Loop 12 and Belt Line Road.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Another beltway around the city upwards of 45 miles (72 km) from Downtown is under plan in Collin County.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Radiating out of Downtown Dallas's freeway loop are the spokes of the area's highway system—Interstates 30, 35E, and 45, US 75, US 77, US 175, SH Spur 366, the Dallas North Tollway, SH 114, US 80, and US 67.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Other major highways around the city include SH 183 and Spur 408.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The recently completed interchange at the intersection of Lyndon B.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Johnson Freeway (I-635) and the Central Expressway (US 75) has five stacks and is aptly called the High Five Interchange.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] It is one of the few five-level interchanges in Dallas and is one of the largest freeway interchanges in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Two commercial airports serve Dallas: Dallas Fort Worth International Airport and Dallas Love Field.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] In addition, Dallas Executive Airport (formerly Redbird Airport), serves as a general aviation airport for the city, and Addison Airport functions similarly just outside the city limits in the suburb of Addison.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Two more general aviation airports are about 35 miles (56 km) north of Dallas in McKinney, and another two are in Fort Worth, on the west side of the metroplex.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Alliance Airport, in far North Fort Worth, is a cargo reliever airport to DFW Airport and general aviation facility.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] DFW Airport is in the suburbs slightly north of and equidistant to Downtown Fort Worth and Downtown Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] In terms of size, DFW International is the largest airport in the state, the second largest in the United States, and ninth largest in the world; DFW International Airport is larger than the island of Manhattan.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] In terms of traffic, DFW Airport is the busiest airport in the state, fourth-busiest in the United States, and eleventh-busiest in the world.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The headquarters of American Airlines, the largest air carrier in the world ahead of United Airlines and Delta Air Lines, is less than one mile (1.6 km) from DFW Airport within Fort Worth's city limits.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Similarly, Love Field is within Dallas's city limits, about 6 miles (10 km) northwest of Downtown, and is headquarters to Southwest Airlines, the largest domestic airline in the United States.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Dallas Area Rapid Transit (DART) is the Dallas-area public transportation authority that provides rail, buses and HOV lanes to commuters.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] DART began operating the first light rail system in Texas in 1996, and it is now the largest operator of light rail in the US.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Today, the system is the seventh-busiest light rail system in the country with approximately 55 stations on 72 miles (116 km) of light rail, and 10 stations on 35 miles (56 km) of commuter rail.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] It includes four light rail lines and a commuter line: the Red Line, the Blue Line, the Green Line, the Orange Line, and the Trinity Railway Express.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The Red Line travels through Oak Cliff, South Dallas, Downtown, Uptown, North Dallas, Richardson and Plano, while the Blue Line goes through Oak Cliff, Downtown, Uptown, East Dallas, Lake Highlands, and Garland.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The Red and Blue lines are conjoined between 8th & Corinth Station in Oak Cliff through Mockingbird Station in North Dallas.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The two lines service Cityplace Station.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The Green Line serves Carrollton, Farmers Branch, Love Field Airport, Stemmons Corridor, Victory Park, Downtown, Deep Ellum, Fair Park, South Dallas, and Pleasant Grove.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The Orange Line initially operated as a peak-service line providing extra capacity on portions of the Green and Red Lines (Bachman Station on the Green Line, through the Downtown transit mall, to Parker Road Station on the Red Line making a "U"-shape).
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] However, the first stage of the Orange Line opened on December 6, 2010, extending its west end from Bachman to Belt Line Station in Irving.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The second and final phase opened in August 2014 and provided DFW Airport with rail service.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] DFW Airport Terminal A station is the terminus for the Orange Line and connects Skylink.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] This provides passengers the convenience of disembarking the DART rail, proceeding to security check-in and immediately boarding Skylink to be quickly transported to their desired terminal.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The Blue Line has also been extended by 4.5 miles (7.2 km) to serve Rowlett at the Rowlett Park & Ride facility.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] In August 2009, the Regional Transportation Council agreed to seek $96 million in federal stimulus dollars for a trolley project in Dallas and Fort Worth.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The Oak Cliff Transit Authority took the lead with leaders envisioning a streetcar line that would link Union Station and the Dallas Convention Center in Downtown to Oak Cliff, Methodist Medical Center, and the Bishop Arts District via the Houston Street Viaduct.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] Dallas was awarded a $23 million TIGER grant towards the $58 million Dallas Streetcar Project in February 2010.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] In addition to light rail, Amtrak's *Texas Eagle* also serves Union Station, providing daily service east to Chicago and west to San Antonio, and thrice-weekly service west to Los Angeles.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The Trinity Rail Express terminates at Union Station and T&P Station.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The city of Dallas has worked to build Sister & Friendship City relationships around the globe.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] These relationships help create and strengthen partnerships between Dallas and the international community.
[src:brooklyn-new-york/dallas-p03] The program aims to build global cooperation at the municipal level by promoting cultural understanding and stimulating economic development between Dallas and its foreign counterparts.
